1
00:00:02,880 --> 00:00:04,480
THE ADVENTURES OF BUSTER BEAR

2
00:00:12,160 --> 00:00:12,960
CHAPTER I

3
00:00:13,600 --> 00:00:16,320
BUSTER BEAR GOES FISHING

4
00:00:16,320 --> 00:00:21,920
Buster Bear yawned as he lay on his comfortable 
bed of leaves and watched the first early morning  

5
00:00:21,920 --> 00:00:29,520
sunbeams creeping through the Green Forest to 
chase out the Black Shadows. Once more he yawned,  

6
00:00:29,520 --> 00:00:35,520
and slowly got to his feet and shook himself. 
Then he walked over to a big pine-tree,  

7
00:00:35,520 --> 00:00:41,360
stood up on his hind legs, reached as high 
up on the trunk of the tree as he could,  

8
00:00:41,360 --> 00:00:48,320
and scratched the bark with his great claws. 
After that he yawned until it seemed as if  

9
00:00:48,320 --> 00:00:53,680
his jaws would crack, and then sat down 
to think what he wanted for breakfast.

10
00:00:54,960 --> 00:01:01,040
While he sat there, trying to make up his mind 
what would taste best, he was listening to the  

11
00:01:01,040 --> 00:01:05,920
sounds that told of the waking of all the 
little people who live in the Green Forest.  

12
00:01:06,560 --> 00:01:09,680
He heard Sammy Jay way off 
in the distance screaming,

13
00:01:09,680 --> 00:01:19,680
"Thief! Thief!" and grinned. "I wonder," thought 
Buster, "if some one has stolen Sammy's breakfast,  

14
00:01:19,680 --> 00:01:25,840
or if he has stolen the breakfast of some 
one else. Probably he is the thief himself."

15
00:01:26,960 --> 00:01:31,600
He heard Chatterer the Red Squirrel scolding 
as fast as he could make his tongue go  

16
00:01:31,600 --> 00:01:34,000
and working himself into a terrible rage.  

17
00:01:34,880 --> 00:01:40,080
"Must be that Chatterer got out of bed 
the wrong way this morning," thought he.

18
00:01:40,960 --> 00:01:47,440
He heard Blacky the Crow cawing at the top of 
his lungs, and he knew by the sound that Blacky  

19
00:01:47,440 --> 00:01:53,200
was getting into mischief of some kind. He heard 
the sweet voices of happy little singers, and they  

20
00:01:53,200 --> 00:02:01,120
were good to hear. But most of all he listened to 
a merry, low, silvery laugh that never stopped but  

21
00:02:01,120 --> 00:02:08,640
went on and on, until he just felt as if he must 
laugh too. It was the voice of the Laughing Brook.

22
00:02:09,280 --> 00:02:14,080
And as Buster listened it suddenly came 
to him just what he wanted for breakfast.

23
00:02:15,040 --> 00:02:22,240
"I'm going fishing," said he in his deep 
grumbly-rumbly voice to no one in particular.  

24
00:02:22,240 --> 00:02:28,080
"Yes, Sir, I'm going fishing. I want 
some fat trout for my breakfast."

25
00:02:29,200 --> 00:02:34,160
He shuffled along over to the Laughing 
Brook, and straight to a little pool of  

26
00:02:34,160 --> 00:02:40,160
which he knew, and as he drew near he took 
the greatest care not to make the teeniest,  

27
00:02:40,160 --> 00:02:47,600
weeniest bit of noise. Now it just happened 
that early as he was, some one was before  

28
00:02:47,600 --> 00:02:52,400
Buster Bear. When he came in sight 
of the little pool, who should

29
00:02:52,400 --> 00:02:57,840
he see but another fisherman there, who 
had already caught a fine fat trout.  

30
00:02:58,800 --> 00:03:04,560
Who was it? Why, Little Joe Otter to be 
sure. He was just climbing up the bank  

31
00:03:04,560 --> 00:03:09,360
with the fat trout in his mouth. Buster 
Bear's own mouth watered as he saw it.  

32
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:14,240
Little Joe sat down on the bank and 
prepared to enjoy his breakfast.  

33
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:20,960
He hadn't seen Buster Bear, and he didn't know 
that he or any one else was anywhere near.

34
00:03:22,240 --> 00:03:31,840
Buster Bear tiptoed up very softly until 
he was right behind Little Joe Otter.

35
00:03:31,840 --> 00:03:37,840
"Woof, woof!" said he in his 
deepest, most grumbly-rumbly voice.  

36
00:03:38,560 --> 00:03:43,920
"That's a very fine looking trout. 
I wouldn't mind if I had it myself."

37
00:03:45,200 --> 00:03:50,080
Little Joe Otter gave a frightened squeal and 
without even turning to see who was speaking  

38
00:03:50,080 --> 00:03:53,840
dropped his fish and dived 
headfirst into the Laughing Brook.

39
00:03:53,840 --> 00:03:57,760
Buster Bear sprang forward 
and with one of his big paws  

40
00:03:57,760 --> 00:04:01,200
caught the fat trout just as it 
was slipping back into the water.

41
00:04:02,080 --> 00:04:07,360
"Here's your trout, Mr. Otter," said he, as 
Little Joe put his head out of water to see  

42
00:04:07,360 --> 00:04:10,560
who had frightened him so. "Come and get it."

43
00:04:10,560 --> 00:04:11,146
Illus Here's your trout, Mr. Otter, said he

44
00:04:11,146 --> 00:04:11,664
Here's your trout, Mr. Otter, said he.

45
00:04:11,665 --> 00:04:11,760
Page 5.

46
00:04:11,760 --> 00:04:18,880
But Little Joe wouldn't. The fact is, he was 
afraid to. He snarled at Buster Bear and called  

47
00:04:18,880 --> 00:04:24,720
him a thief and everything bad he could think 
of. Buster didn't seem to mind. He chuckled as  

48
00:04:24,720 --> 00:04:30,240
if he thought it all a great joke and repeated his 
invitation to Little Joe to come and get his fish.  

49
00:04:31,120 --> 00:04:36,400
But Little Joe just turned his back and went 
off down the Laughing Brook in a great rage.

50
00:04:37,440 --> 00:04:42,640
"It's too bad to waste such a fine 
fish," said Buster thoughtfully.  

51
00:04:43,200 --> 00:04:50,400
"I wonder what I'd better do with it." And 
while he was wondering, he ate it all up.  

52
00:04:51,200 --> 00:04:55,840
Then he started down the Laughing 
Brook to try to catch some for himself.

53
00:04:56,560 --> 00:04:57,360
CHAPTER II

54
00:05:00,960 --> 00:05:03,760
LITTLE JOE OTTER GETS EVEN WITH BUSTER BEAR

55
00:05:04,880 --> 00:05:10,720
Little Joe Otter was in a terrible rage. It 
was a bad beginning for a beautiful day and  

56
00:05:10,720 --> 00:05:16,240
Little Joe knew it. But who wouldn't be in 
a rage if his breakfast was taken from him  

57
00:05:16,240 --> 00:05:22,800
just as he was about to eat it? Anyway, that 
is what Little Joe told Billy Mink. Perhaps he  

58
00:05:22,800 --> 00:05:29,040
didn't tell it quite exactly as it was, but you 
know he was very badly frightened at the time.

59
00:05:30,240 --> 00:05:34,240
"I was sitting on the bank of the Laughing 
Brook beside one of the little pools,"

60
00:05:34,880 --> 00:05:40,640
he told Billy Mink, "and was just going to eat 
a fat trout I had caught, when who should come  

61
00:05:40,640 --> 00:05:46,720
along but that great big bully, Buster Bear. 
He took that fat trout away from me and ate it  

62
00:05:46,720 --> 00:05:53,600
just as if it belonged to him! I hate him! If I 
live long enough I'm going to get even with him!"

63
00:05:53,600 --> 00:05:58,560
Of course that wasn't nice talk 
and anything but a nice spirit,  

64
00:05:58,560 --> 00:06:02,240
but Little Joe Otter's temper 
is sometimes pretty short,  

65
00:06:02,240 --> 00:06:06,800
especially when he is hungry, and this 
time he had had no breakfast, you know.

66
00:06:07,680 --> 00:06:13,920
Buster Bear hadn't actually taken the fish away 
from Little Joe. But looking at the matter as  

67
00:06:13,920 --> 00:06:19,760
Little Joe did, it amounted to the same thing. 
You see, Buster knew perfectly well when he  

68
00:06:19,760 --> 00:06:25,920
invited Little Joe to come back and get it that 
Little Joe wouldn't dare do anything of the kind.

69
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:29,360
"Where is he now?" asked Billy Mink.

70
00:06:30,080 --> 00:06:35,600
"He's somewhere up the Laughing Brook. 
I wish he'd fall in and get drowned!"

71
00:06:35,600 --> 00:06:36,640
snapped Little Joe.

72
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:44,240
Billy Mink just had to laugh. The idea of great 
big Buster Bear getting drowned in the Laughing  

73
00:06:44,240 --> 00:06:50,880
Brook was too funny. There wasn't water enough 
in it anywhere except down in the Smiling Pool,  

74
00:06:50,880 --> 00:06:55,360
and that was on the Green Meadows, 
where Buster had never been known to go.  

75
00:06:56,160 --> 00:06:59,120
"Let's go see what he is doing," said Billy Mink.

76
00:06:59,920 --> 00:07:05,920
At first Little Joe didn't want to, but at 
last his curiosity got the better of his fear,

77
00:07:05,920 --> 00:07:09,920
and he agreed. So the two 
little brown-coated scamps  

78
00:07:09,920 --> 00:07:14,800
turned down the Laughing Brook, taking 
the greatest care to keep out of sight  

79
00:07:14,800 --> 00:07:22,400
themselves. They had gone only a little way 
when Billy Mink whispered: "Sh-h! There he is."

80
00:07:23,360 --> 00:07:24,080
Sure enough,  

81
00:07:24,640 --> 00:07:30,960
there was Buster Bear sitting close beside a 
little pool and looking into it very intently.

82
00:07:30,960 --> 00:07:31,840
"What's he doing?"  

83
00:07:32,480 --> 00:07:37,520
asked Little Joe Otter, as Buster Bear 
sat for the longest time without moving.

84
00:07:38,320 --> 00:07:43,520
Just then one of Buster's big paws 
went into the water as quick as a flash  

85
00:07:43,520 --> 00:07:46,960
and scooped out a trout 
that had ventured too near.

86
00:07:47,680 --> 00:07:50,960
"He's fishing!" exclaimed Billy Mink.

87
00:07:50,960 --> 00:07:56,640
And that is just what Buster Bear was doing, 
and it was very plain to see that he was having  

88
00:07:56,640 --> 00:08:02,080
great fun. When he had eaten the trout he had 
caught, he moved along to the next little pool.

89
00:08:03,200 --> 00:08:10,400
"They are our fish!" said Little Joe fiercely. 
"He has no business catching our fish!"

90
00:08:11,200 --> 00:08:15,120
"I don't see how we are going 
to stop him," said Billy Mink.

91
00:08:15,120 --> 00:08:21,600
"I do!" cried Little Joe, into whose head 
an idea had just popped. "I'm going to drive  

92
00:08:21,600 --> 00:08:25,680
all the fish out of the little 
pools and muddy the water all up.  

93
00:08:25,680 --> 00:08:30,480
Then we'll see how many fish he will get! 
Just you watch me get even with Buster Bear."

94
00:08:31,280 --> 00:08:38,000
Little Joe slipped swiftly into the water and swam 
straight to the little pool that Buster Bear would  

95
00:08:38,000 --> 00:08:44,560
try next. He frightened the fish so that they 
fled in every direction. Then he stirred up  

96
00:08:44,560 --> 00:08:51,920
the mud until the water was so dirty that Buster 
couldn't have seen a fish right under his nose. He  

97
00:08:51,920 --> 00:08:59,120
did the same thing in the next pool and the next. 
Buster Bear's fishing was spoiled for that day.

98
00:09:01,360 --> 00:09:02,160
CHAPTER III

99
00:09:05,840 --> 00:09:07,840
BUSTER BEAR IS GREATLY PUZZLED

100
00:09:08,960 --> 00:09:14,000
Buster Bear hadn't enjoyed himself so much 
since he came to the Green Forest to live.  

101
00:09:14,720 --> 00:09:19,600
His fun began when he surprised Little Joe 
Otter on the bank of a little pool in the  

102
00:09:19,600 --> 00:09:25,200
Laughing Brook and Little Joe was so frightened 
that he dropped a fat trout he had just caught.  

103
00:09:25,840 --> 00:09:31,280
It had seemed like a great joke to Buster Bear, 
and he had chuckled over it all the time he was  

104
00:09:31,280 --> 00:09:37,120
eating the fat trout. When he had finished 
it, he started on to do some fishing himself.

105
00:09:38,160 --> 00:09:44,400
Presently he came to another little pool. 
He stole up to it very, very softly,  

106
00:09:44,400 --> 00:09:50,560
so as not to frighten the fish. Then he sat 
down close to the edge of it and didn't move.

107
00:09:51,520 --> 00:09:55,600
Buster learned a long time ago that 
a fisherman must be patient unless,  

108
00:09:56,160 --> 00:10:01,520
like Little Joe Otter, he is just as much 
at home in the water as the fish themselves,  

109
00:10:01,520 --> 00:10:08,400
and can swim fast enough to catch them by chasing 
them. So he didn't move so much as an eye lash.  

110
00:10:09,120 --> 00:10:13,280
He was so still that he looked 
almost like the stump of an old tree.

111
00:10:14,320 --> 00:10:20,720
Perhaps that is what the fish thought he was, for 
pretty soon, two or three swam right in close to  

112
00:10:20,720 --> 00:10:28,000
where he was sitting. Now Buster Bear may be big 
and clumsy looking, but there isn't anything that  

113
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:34,080
can move much quicker than one of those big paws 
of his when he wants it to. One of them moved now,  

114
00:10:34,080 --> 00:10:39,280
and quicker than a wink had scooped one 
of those foolish fish out on to the bank.

115
00:10:40,720 --> 00:10:46,400
Buster's little eyes twinkled, and he smacked 
his lips as he moved on to the next little pool,  

116
00:10:46,400 --> 00:10:50,000
for he knew that it was of no use 
to stay longer at the first one.  

117
00:10:50,640 --> 00:10:55,280
The fish were so frightened that they 
wouldn't come back for a long, long time.  

118
00:10:56,240 --> 00:11:02,000
At the next little pool the same thing 
happened. By this time Buster Bear was  

119
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:07,680
in fine spirits. It was fun to catch the 
fish, and it was still more fun to eat them.  

120
00:11:08,320 --> 00:11:16,480
What finer breakfast could any one have than 
fresh-caught trout? No wonder he felt good! But it  

121
00:11:16,480 --> 00:11:22,480
takes more than three trout to fill Buster Bear's 
stomach, so he kept on to the next little pool.

122
00:11:23,440 --> 00:11:29,440
But this little pool, instead of being beautiful 
and clear so that Buster could see right to the  

123
00:11:29,440 --> 00:11:34,720
bottom of it and so tell if there were any 
fish there, was so muddy that he couldn't  

124
00:11:34,720 --> 00:11:42,080
see into it at all. It looked as if some one 
had just stirred up all the mud at the bottom.

125
00:11:42,080 --> 00:11:47,360
"Huh!" said Buster Bear. "It's 
of no use to try to fish here.  

126
00:11:47,920 --> 00:11:52,720
I would just waste my time. 
I'll try the next pool."

127
00:11:53,920 --> 00:11:59,760
So he went on to the next little pool. 
He found this just as muddy as the other.

128
00:12:00,640 --> 00:12:08,560
Then he went on to another, and this was no 
better. Buster sat down and scratched his head. It  

129
00:12:08,560 --> 00:12:17,600
was puzzling. Yes, Sir, it was puzzling. He looked 
this way and he looked that way suspiciously,  

130
00:12:18,160 --> 00:12:25,120
but there was no one to be seen. Everything was 
still save for the laughter of the Laughing Brook.  

131
00:12:26,080 --> 00:12:30,800
Somehow, it seemed to Buster as 
if the Brook were laughing at him.

132
00:12:31,600 --> 00:12:35,280
"It's very curious," muttered Buster,  

133
00:12:36,160 --> 00:12:45,360
"very curious indeed. It looks as if my fishing 
is spoiled for to-day. I don't understand it at  

134
00:12:45,360 --> 00:12:52,080
all. It's lucky I caught what I did. It 
looks as if somebody is trying to—ha!"  

135
00:12:54,960 --> 00:13:00,960
A sudden thought had popped into his head. 
Then he began to chuckle and finally to laugh.  

136
00:13:01,840 --> 00:13:09,680
"I do believe that scamp Joe Otter is trying 
to get even with me for eating that fat trout!"

137
00:13:10,960 --> 00:13:17,520
And then, because Buster Bear always enjoys 
a good joke even when it is on himself,  

138
00:13:17,520 --> 00:13:21,520
he laughed until he had to hold 
his sides, which is a whole lot  

139
00:13:21,520 --> 00:13:28,560
better than going off in a rage as Little 
Joe Otter had done. "You're pretty smart, Mr.

140
00:13:28,560 --> 00:13:36,960
Otter! You're pretty smart, but there are other 
people who are smart too," said Buster Bear,  

141
00:13:36,960 --> 00:13:42,960
and still chuckling, he went off to think up 
a plan to get the best of Little Joe Otter.

142
00:13:44,880 --> 00:13:47,840
CHAPTER IV

143
00:13:50,880 --> 00:13:52,960
LITTLE JOE OTTER SUPPLIES BUSTER

144
00:13:52,960 --> 00:13:54,000
BEAR WITH A BREAKFAST

145
00:13:55,440 --> 00:13:57,680
Getting even just for spite

146
00:13:57,680 --> 00:13:59,040
Doesn't always pay.

147
00:13:59,920 --> 00:14:02,080
Fact is, it is very apt

148
00:14:02,080 --> 00:14:03,520
To work the other way.

149
00:14:04,400 --> 00:14:09,120
That is just how it came about that Little 
Joe Otter furnished Buster Bear with the  

150
00:14:09,120 --> 00:14:17,200
best breakfast he had had for a long time. He 
didn't mean to do it. Oh, my, no! The truth is,  

151
00:14:17,200 --> 00:14:22,000
he thought all the time that he was preventing 
Buster Bear from getting a breakfast.  

152
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:28,000
You see he wasn't well enough acquainted with 
Buster to know that Buster is quite as smart  

153
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:35,200
as he is, and perhaps a little bit smarter. 
Spite and selfishness were at the bottom of it.  

154
00:14:35,200 --> 00:14:41,440
You see Little Joe and Billy Mink had had all the 
fishing in the Laughing Brook to themselves so  

155
00:14:41,440 --> 00:14:48,480
long that they thought no one else had any right 
to fish there. To be sure Bobby Coon caught a few  

156
00:14:48,480 --> 00:14:55,440
little fish there, but they didn't mind Bobby. 
Farmer Brown's boy fished there too, sometimes,  

157
00:14:55,440 --> 00:15:00,720
and this always made Little Joe and Billy Mink 
very angry, but they were so afraid of him that  

158
00:15:00,720 --> 00:15:06,960
they didn't dare do anything about it. But when 
they discovered that Buster Bear was a fisherman,  

159
00:15:06,960 --> 00:15:12,960
they made up their minds that something had 
got to be done. At least, Little Joe did.

160
00:15:13,840 --> 00:15:17,440
"He'll try it again to-morrow 
morning," said Little Joe.  

161
00:15:18,080 --> 00:15:25,840
"I'll keep watch, and as soon as I see him coming, 
I'll drive out all the fish, just as I did to-day.  

162
00:15:26,640 --> 00:15:29,920
I guess that'll teach him to let our fish alone."

163
00:15:31,600 --> 00:15:36,960
So the next morning Little Joe hid before 
daylight close by the little pool where  

164
00:15:36,960 --> 00:15:43,840
Buster Bear had given him such a fright. Sure 
enough, just as the Jolly Sunbeams began to  

165
00:15:43,840 --> 00:15:49,120
creep through the Green Forest, he saw Buster 
Bear coming straight over to the little pool.  

166
00:15:50,160 --> 00:15:55,600
Little Joe slipped into the water and 
chased all the fish out of the little pool,  

167
00:15:55,600 --> 00:16:00,720
and stirred up the mud on the bottom so that the 
water was so muddy that the bottom couldn't be  

168
00:16:00,720 --> 00:16:06,160
seen at all. Then he hurried down to the 
next little pool and did the same thing.

169
00:16:06,800 --> 00:16:11,760
Now Buster Bear is very smart. You 
know he had guessed the day before who

170
00:16:11,760 --> 00:16:17,360
had spoiled his fishing. So this morning he 
only went far enough to make sure that if  

171
00:16:17,360 --> 00:16:22,720
Little Joe were watching for him, as he was 
sure he would be, he would see him coming.  

172
00:16:23,440 --> 00:16:30,000
Then, instead of keeping on to the little pool, 
he hurried to a place way down the Laughing Brook,  

173
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:36,560
where the water was very shallow, hardly over 
his feet, and there he sat chuckling to himself.  

174
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:40,480
Things happened just as he had expected.  

175
00:16:41,280 --> 00:16:47,120
The frightened fish Little Joe chased out of 
the little pools up above swam down the Laughing  

176
00:16:47,120 --> 00:16:53,440
Brook, because, you know, Little Joe was behind 
them, and there was nowhere else for them to go.  

177
00:16:54,240 --> 00:17:00,000
When they came to the place where Buster was 
waiting, all he had to do was to scoop them out  

178
00:17:00,000 --> 00:17:06,080
on to the bank. It was great fun. It didn't take 
Buster long to catch all the fish he could eat.

179
00:17:06,720 --> 00:17:09,840
Then he saved a nice fat trout and waited.

180
00:17:11,040 --> 00:17:17,120
By and by along came Little Joe Otter, chuckling 
to think how he had spoiled Buster Bear's fishing.  

181
00:17:17,760 --> 00:17:21,520
He was so intent on looking behind 
him to see if Buster was coming  

182
00:17:21,520 --> 00:17:24,880
that he didn't see Buster 
waiting there until he spoke.

183
00:17:26,160 --> 00:17:29,840
"I'm much obliged for the fine 
breakfast you have given me,"  

184
00:17:30,480 --> 00:17:37,920
said Buster in his deepest, most grumbly-rumbly 
voice. "I've saved a fat trout for you to  

185
00:17:37,920 --> 00:17:43,520
make up for the one I ate yesterday. I 
hope we'll go fishing together often."

186
00:17:44,560 --> 00:17:51,120
Then he went off laughing fit to kill himself. 
Little Joe couldn't find a word to say.  

187
00:17:51,120 --> 00:17:58,160
He was so surprised and angry that he went 
off by himself and sulked. And Billy Mink,  

188
00:17:58,800 --> 00:18:02,400
who had been watching, ate the fat trout.

189
00:18:04,160 --> 00:18:04,960
CHAPTER V

190
00:18:14,960 --> 00:18:17,520
GRANDFATHER FROG'S COMMON-SENSE

191
00:18:18,320 --> 00:18:24,400
There is nothing quite like common sense to smooth 
out troubles. People who have plenty of just plain  

192
00:18:24,400 --> 00:18:30,720
common sense are often thought to be very wise. 
Their neighbors look up to them and are forever  

193
00:18:30,720 --> 00:18:37,200
running to them for advice, and they are very much 
respected. That is the way with Grandfather Frog.  

194
00:18:37,920 --> 00:18:44,800
He is very old and very wise. Anyway, that 
is what his neighbors think. The truth is,  

195
00:18:44,800 --> 00:18:51,120
he simply has a lot of common sense, which 
after all is the very best kind of wisdom.

196
00:18:51,840 --> 00:18:57,360
Now when Little Joe Otter found that Buster Bear 
had been too smart for him and that instead of  

197
00:18:57,360 --> 00:19:03,280
spoiling Buster's fishing in the Laughing Brook 
he had really made it easier for Buster to catch  

198
00:19:03,280 --> 00:19:10,080
all the fish he wanted, Little Joe went off 
down to the Smiling Pool in a great rage.

199
00:19:10,080 --> 00:19:13,280
Billy Mink stopped long enough to eat the fat fish  

200
00:19:13,280 --> 00:19:18,080
Buster had left on the bank and then 
he too went down to the Smiling Pool.

201
00:19:19,440 --> 00:19:26,240
When Little Joe Otter and Billy Mink reached the 
Smiling Pool, they climbed up on the Big Rock, and  

202
00:19:26,240 --> 00:19:32,720
there Little Joe sulked and sulked, until finally 
Grandfather Frog asked what the matter was.  

203
00:19:33,600 --> 00:19:39,840
Little Joe wouldn't tell, but Billy Mink told 
the whole story. When he told how Buster had  

204
00:19:39,840 --> 00:19:47,360
been too smart for Little Joe, it tickled him so 
that Billy had to laugh in spite of himself. So  

205
00:19:47,360 --> 00:19:54,640
did Grandfather Frog. So did Jerry Muskrat, who 
had been listening. Of course this made Little  

206
00:19:54,640 --> 00:20:01,600
Joe angrier than ever. He said a lot of unkind 
things about Buster Bear and about Billy Mink  

207
00:20:01,600 --> 00:20:08,000
and Grandfather Frog and Jerry Muskrat, because 
they had laughed at the smartness of Buster.

208
00:20:09,200 --> 00:20:13,600
"He's nothing but a great big bully 
and thief!" declared Little Joe.

209
00:20:14,320 --> 00:20:20,480
"Chug-a-rum! He may be a bully, because 
great big people are very apt to be bullies,  

210
00:20:20,480 --> 00:20:26,160
and though I haven't seen him, I guess Buster 
Bear is big enough from all I have heard,  

211
00:20:26,720 --> 00:20:30,640
but I don't see how he is a 
thief," said Grandfather Frog.

212
00:20:31,680 --> 00:20:37,280
"Didn't he catch my fish and eat them?" snapped 
Little Joe. "Doesn't that make him a thief?"

213
00:20:38,080 --> 00:20:41,600
"They were no more your fish 
than mine," protested Billy Mink.

214
00:20:42,400 --> 00:20:48,080
"Well, our fish, then! He stole our 
fish, if you like that any better.  

215
00:20:48,720 --> 00:20:52,960
That makes him just as much a thief, 
doesn't it?" growled Little Joe.

216
00:20:54,160 --> 00:21:01,120
Grandfather Frog looked up at jolly, round, 
bright Mr. Sun and slowly winked one of his great,  

217
00:21:01,120 --> 00:21:07,760
goggly eyes. "There comes a foolish green 
fly," said he. "Who does he belong to?"

218
00:21:09,040 --> 00:21:14,720
"Nobody!" snapped Little Joe. "What have 
foolish green flies got to do with my

219
00:21:15,520 --> 00:21:17,440
—I mean our fish?"

220
00:21:18,720 --> 00:21:23,200
"Nothing, nothing at all," 
replied Grandfather Frog mildly.  

221
00:21:23,920 --> 00:21:28,960
"I was just hoping that he would come near 
enough for me to snap him up; then he would  

222
00:21:28,960 --> 00:21:37,200
belong to me. As long as he doesn't, he doesn't 
belong to any one. I suppose that if Buster Bear  

223
00:21:37,200 --> 00:21:43,840
should happen along and catch him, he would 
be stealing from me, according to Little Joe."

224
00:21:44,640 --> 00:21:50,400
"Of course not! What a silly idea! 
You're getting foolish in your old age,"

225
00:21:50,960 --> 00:21:52,080
retorted Little Joe.

226
00:21:52,960 --> 00:21:56,720
"Can you tell me the difference between 
the fish that you haven't caught  

227
00:21:56,720 --> 00:22:01,520
and the foolish green flies that I 
haven't caught?" asked Grandfather Frog.

228
00:22:02,960 --> 00:22:05,440
Little Joe couldn't find a word to say.

229
00:22:06,480 --> 00:22:11,280
"You take my advice, Little Joe 
Otter," continued Grandfather Frog,  

230
00:22:11,280 --> 00:22:16,720
"and always make friends with those who are 
bigger and stronger and smarter than you are.

231
00:22:17,600 --> 00:22:19,680
You'll find it pays."

