CHAPTER VI

236
00:22:26,160 --> 00:22:28,560
LITTLE JOE OTTER TAKES GRANDFATHER

237
00:22:28,560 --> 00:22:29,520
FROG'S ADVICE

238
00:22:30,640 --> 00:22:32,800
Who makes an enemy a friend,

239
00:22:32,800 --> 00:22:35,120
To fear and worry puts an end.

240
00:22:36,400 --> 00:22:40,480
Little Joe Otter found that out when 
he took Grandfather Frog's advice.  

241
00:22:41,360 --> 00:22:46,160
He wouldn't have admitted that he was afraid 
of Buster Bear. No one ever likes to admit  

242
00:22:46,160 --> 00:22:52,640
being afraid, least of all Little Joe Otter. And 
really Little Joe has a great deal of courage.  

243
00:22:53,280 --> 00:22:58,640
Very few of the little people of the Green Forest 
or the Green Meadows would willingly quarrel with  

244
00:22:58,640 --> 00:23:05,440
him, for Little Joe is a great fighter when he has 
to fight. As for all those who live in or along  

245
00:23:05,440 --> 00:23:11,360
the Laughing Brook or in the Smiling Pool, they 
let Little Joe have his own way in everything.

246
00:23:12,240 --> 00:23:20,000
Now having one's own way too much is a bad thing. 
It is apt to make one selfish and thoughtless  

247
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:27,840
of other people and very hard to get along with. 
Little Joe Otter had his way too much. Grandfather  

248
00:23:27,840 --> 00:23:33,520
Frog knew it and shook his head very soberly 
when Little Joe had been disrespectful to him.

249
00:23:34,560 --> 00:23:42,960
"Too bad. Too bad! Too bad! Chug-a-rum! It is too 
bad that such a fine young fellow as Little Joe  

250
00:23:42,960 --> 00:23:47,120
should spoil a good disposition 
by such selfish heedlessness.

251
00:23:48,160 --> 00:23:49,840
Too bad," said he.

252
00:23:50,880 --> 00:23:55,040
So, though he didn't let on 
that it was so, Grandfather Frog  

253
00:23:55,040 --> 00:24:00,720
really was delighted when he heard how Buster 
Bear had been too smart for Little Joe Otter.  

254
00:24:00,720 --> 00:24:04,560
It tickled him so that he had 
hard work to keep a straight face.  

255
00:24:05,920 --> 00:24:11,520
But he did and was as grave and solemn 
as you please as he advised Little Joe  

256
00:24:11,520 --> 00:24:16,400
always to make friends with any one who was 
bigger and stronger and smarter than he.  

257
00:24:17,520 --> 00:24:24,000
That was good common sense advice, but Little Joe 
just sniffed and went off declaring that he would  

258
00:24:24,000 --> 00:24:31,360
get even with Buster Bear yet. Now Little Joe is 
good-natured and full of fun as a rule, and after  

259
00:24:31,360 --> 00:24:37,600
he had reached home and his temper had cooled off 
a little, he began to see the joke on himself,—how  

260
00:24:38,560 --> 00:24:44,080
when he had worked so hard to frighten the fish 
in the little pools of the Laughing Brook so that  

261
00:24:44,080 --> 00:24:51,120
Buster Bear should not catch any, he had all the 
time been driving them right into Buster's paws.  

262
00:24:52,160 --> 00:24:59,120
By and by he grinned. It was a little 
sheepish grin at first, but at last it

263
00:24:59,120 --> 00:25:00,560
grew into a laugh.

264
00:25:02,080 --> 00:25:06,400
"I believe," said Little Joe as he 
wiped tears of laughter from his eyes,  

265
00:25:06,400 --> 00:25:11,040
"that Grandfather Frog is right, 
and that the best thing I can do  

266
00:25:11,040 --> 00:25:15,360
is to make friends with Buster Bear. 
I'll try it to-morrow morning."

267
00:25:16,800 --> 00:25:22,480
So very early the next morning Little Joe Otter 
went to the best fishing pool he knew of in the  

268
00:25:22,480 --> 00:25:29,680
Laughing Brook, and there he caught the biggest 
trout he could find. It was so big and fat that  

269
00:25:29,680 --> 00:25:35,760
it made Little Joe's mouth water, for you know 
fat trout are his favorite food. But he didn't  

270
00:25:35,760 --> 00:25:43,120
take so much as one bite. Instead he carefully 
laid it on an old log where Buster Bear would  

271
00:25:43,120 --> 00:25:49,120
be sure to see it if he should come along that 
way. Then he hid near by, where he could watch.  

272
00:25:50,400 --> 00:25:56,480
Buster was late that morning. It seemed to 
Little Joe that he never would come. Once  

273
00:25:56,480 --> 00:26:02,240
he nearly lost the fish. He had turned his head 
for just a minute, and when he looked back again,  

274
00:26:02,240 --> 00:26:07,760
the trout was nowhere to be seen. Buster 
couldn't have stolen up and taken it,  

275
00:26:07,760 --> 00:26:11,200
because such a big fellow couldn't 
possibly have gotten out of sight again.

276
00:26:12,400 --> 00:26:15,600
Little Joe darted over to the 
log and looked on the other side.  

277
00:26:16,400 --> 00:26:24,080
There was the fat trout, and there also was 
Little Joe's smallest cousin, Shadow the Weasel,  

278
00:26:24,080 --> 00:26:30,720
who is a great thief and altogether 
bad. Little Joe sprang at him angrily,  

279
00:26:30,720 --> 00:26:36,800
but Shadow was too quick and darted away. Little 
Joe put the fish back on the log and waited.

280
00:26:37,680 --> 00:26:45,120
This time he didn't take his eyes off it. At 
last, when he was almost ready to give up, he saw  

281
00:26:45,120 --> 00:26:52,640
Buster Bear shuffling along towards the Laughing 
Brook. Suddenly Buster stopped and sniffed.  

282
00:26:53,440 --> 00:27:00,160
One of the Merry Little Breezes had carried the 
scent of that fat trout over to him. Then he came  

283
00:27:00,160 --> 00:27:06,480
straight over to where the fish lay, his nose 
wrinkling, and his eyes twinkling with pleasure.

284
00:27:08,160 --> 00:27:11,520
"Now I wonder who was so thoughtful  

285
00:27:11,520 --> 00:27:16,480
as to leave this fine breakfast 
ready for me," said he out loud.

286
00:27:17,600 --> 00:27:23,760
"Me," said Little Joe in a rather faint 
voice. "I caught it especially for you."

287
00:27:25,920 --> 00:27:29,040
"Thank you," replied Buster,  

288
00:27:29,040 --> 00:27:34,400
and his eyes twinkled more than ever. 
"I think we are going to be friends."

289
00:27:35,520 --> 00:27:39,600
"I—I hope so," replied Little Joe.

290
00:27:41,440 --> 00:27:42,320
CHAPTER VII

291
00:27:45,840 --> 00:27:48,000
FARMER BROWN'S BOY HAS NO LUCK

292
00:27:48,000 --> 00:27:48,400
AT ALL

293
00:27:49,600 --> 00:27:55,280
Farmer Brown's boy tramped through the Green 
Forest, whistling merrily. He always whistles  

294
00:27:55,280 --> 00:27:59,520
when he feels light-hearted, and he always 
feels light-hearted when he goes fishing.  

295
00:28:00,240 --> 00:28:05,200
You see, he is just as fond of fishing 
as is Little Joe Otter or Billy Mink  

296
00:28:05,200 --> 00:28:11,120
or Buster Bear. And now he was making his way 
through the Green Forest to the Laughing Brook,  

297
00:28:11,120 --> 00:28:16,480
sure that by the time he had followed it down 
to the Smiling Pool he would have a fine lot of  

298
00:28:16,480 --> 00:28:22,320
trout to take home. He knew every pool in the 
Laughing Brook where the trout love to hide,  

299
00:28:22,320 --> 00:28:27,120
did Farmer Brown's boy, and it was just the kind 
of a morning when the trout should be hungry.  

300
00:28:27,840 --> 00:28:31,840
So he whistled as he tramped along, 
and his whistle was good to hear.

301
00:28:33,280 --> 00:28:38,000
When he reached the first little pool he 
baited his hook very carefully and then,  

302
00:28:38,000 --> 00:28:43,360
taking the greatest care to keep out of sight 
of any trout that might be in the little pool,  

303
00:28:43,360 --> 00:28:51,040
he began to fish. Now Farmer Brown's boy learned 
a long time ago that to be a successful fisherman  

304
00:28:51,040 --> 00:28:57,040
one must have a great deal of patience, so though 
he didn't get a bite right away as he had expected  

305
00:28:57,040 --> 00:29:03,520
to, he wasn't the least bit discouraged. 
He kept very quiet and fished and fished,  

306
00:29:03,520 --> 00:29:06,640
patiently waiting for a 
foolish trout to take his hook.  

307
00:29:07,680 --> 00:29:14,240
But he didn't get so much as a nibble. "Either the 
trout have lost their appetite or they have grown  

308
00:29:14,240 --> 00:29:21,120
very wise," muttered Farmer Brown's boy, as after 
a long time he moved on to the next little pool.

309
00:29:22,560 --> 00:29:28,240
There the same thing happened. He 
was very patient, very, very patient,  

310
00:29:28,800 --> 00:29:35,760
but his patience brought no reward, not so much 
as the faintest kind of a nibble. Farmer Brown's  

311
00:29:35,760 --> 00:29:42,640
boy trudged on to the next pool, and there was a 
puzzled frown on his freckled face. Such a thing  

312
00:29:42,640 --> 00:29:49,360
never had happened before. He didn't know what to 
make of it. All the night before he had dreamed  

313
00:29:49,360 --> 00:29:55,280
about the delicious dinner of fried trout he would 
have the next day, and now—well, if he didn't  

314
00:29:55,280 --> 00:30:00,560
catch some trout pretty soon, that splendid 
dinner would never be anything but a dream.

315
00:30:01,360 --> 00:30:04,320
"If I didn't know that nobody 
else comes fishing here,  

316
00:30:04,960 --> 00:30:10,560
I should think that somebody had been here this 
very morning and caught all the fish or else  

317
00:30:10,560 --> 00:30:16,560
frightened them so that they are all in hiding," 
said he, as he trudged on to the next little pool.  

318
00:30:17,920 --> 00:30:24,320
"I never had such bad luck in 
all my life before. Hello! What's

319
00:30:24,320 --> 00:30:24,720
this?"

320
00:30:25,760 --> 00:30:32,960
There, on the bank beside the little pool, were 
the heads of three trout. Farmer Brown's boy  

321
00:30:32,960 --> 00:30:39,840
scowled down at them more puzzled than 
ever. "Somebody has been fishing here,  

322
00:30:39,840 --> 00:30:45,680
and they have had better luck than I have," 
thought he. He looked up the Laughing Brook  

323
00:30:45,680 --> 00:30:52,720
and down the Laughing Brook and this way and that 
way, but no one was to be seen. Then he picked up  

324
00:30:52,720 --> 00:30:58,240
one of the little heads and looked at it 
sharply. "It wasn't cut off with a knife;  

325
00:30:58,240 --> 00:31:05,760
it was bitten off!" he exclaimed. "I wonder now if 
Billy Mink is the scamp who has spoiled my fun."

326
00:31:07,280 --> 00:31:10,800
Thereafter he kept a sharp 
lookout for signs of Billy Mink,  

327
00:31:10,800 --> 00:31:18,080
but though he found two or three more trout heads, 
he saw no other signs and he caught no fish.  

328
00:31:18,080 --> 00:31:22,960
This puzzled him more than ever. It didn't 
seem possible that such a little fellow as  

329
00:31:22,960 --> 00:31:27,840
Billy Mink could have caught or frightened 
all the fish or have eaten so many.

330
00:31:28,640 --> 00:31:33,200
Besides, he didn't remember ever having 
known Billy to leave heads around that way.  

331
00:31:34,000 --> 00:31:38,480
Billy sometimes catches more fish than he 
can eat, but then he usually hides them.  

332
00:31:39,280 --> 00:31:43,840
The farther he went down the Laughing 
Brook, the more puzzled Farmer Brown's  

333
00:31:43,840 --> 00:31:49,360
boy grew. It made him feel very queer. He 
would have felt still more queer if he had  

334
00:31:49,360 --> 00:31:55,040
known that all the time two other fishermen 
who had been before him were watching him  

335
00:31:55,040 --> 00:32:00,880
and chuckling to themselves. They 
were Little Joe Otter and Buster Bear.

336
00:32:02,480 --> 00:32:03,360
CHAPTER VIII

337
00:32:06,400 --> 00:32:08,320
FARMER BROWN'S BOY FEELS HIS

338
00:32:08,320 --> 00:32:09,040
HAIR RISE

339
00:32:10,080 --> 00:32:12,800
'Twas just a sudden odd surprise

340
00:32:12,800 --> 00:32:15,360
Made Farmer Brown's boy's hair to rise.

341
00:32:16,640 --> 00:32:22,560
That's a funny thing for hair to do—rise up all 
of a sudden—isn't it? But that is just what the  

342
00:32:22,560 --> 00:32:28,640
hair on Farmer Brown's boy's head did the day he 
went fishing in the Laughing Brook and had no luck  

343
00:32:28,640 --> 00:32:36,400
at all. There are just two things that make hair 
rise—anger and fear. Anger sometimes makes the  

344
00:32:36,400 --> 00:32:42,240
hair on the back and neck of Bowser the Hound and 
of some other little people bristle and stand up,  

345
00:32:42,240 --> 00:32:48,240
and you know the hair on the tail of Black Pussy 
stands on end until her tail looks twice as big  

346
00:32:48,240 --> 00:32:55,360
as it really is. Both anger and fear make it do 
that. But there is only one thing that can make  

347
00:32:55,360 --> 00:33:01,600
the hair on the head of Farmer Brown's boy rise, 
and as it isn't anger, of course it must be fear.

348
00:33:02,720 --> 00:33:08,320
It never had happened before. You see, there 
isn't much of anything that Farmer Brown's boy is  

349
00:33:08,320 --> 00:33:13,120
really afraid of. Perhaps he wouldn't have 
been afraid this time if it hadn't been for  

350
00:33:13,120 --> 00:33:19,520
the surprise of what he found. You see when he 
had found the heads of those trout on the bank  

351
00:33:19,520 --> 00:33:24,720
he knew right away that some one else had been 
fishing, and that was why he couldn't catch any;  

352
00:33:25,360 --> 00:33:30,560
but it didn't seem possible that little 
Billy Mink could have eaten all those trout,  

353
00:33:30,560 --> 00:33:37,840
and Farmer Brown's boy didn't once think of Little 
Joe Otter, and so he was very, very much puzzled.

354
00:33:38,800 --> 00:33:42,640
He was turning it all over in his 
mind and studying what it could mean,  

355
00:33:42,640 --> 00:33:46,240
when he came to a little muddy place 
on the bank of the Laughing Brook,  

356
00:33:46,880 --> 00:33:53,280
and there he saw something that made his eyes 
look as if they would pop right out of his head,  

357
00:33:53,280 --> 00:33:56,320
and it was right then that he felt his hair rise.  

358
00:33:57,040 --> 00:34:04,320
Anyway, that is what he said when he told about it 
afterward. What was it he saw? What do you think?  

359
00:34:05,200 --> 00:34:12,480
Why, it was a footprint in the soft mud. 
Yes, Sir, that's what it was, and all it was.  

360
00:34:13,280 --> 00:34:20,720
But it was the biggest footprint Farmer 
Brown's boy ever had seen, and it looked  

361
00:34:20,720 --> 00:34:27,920
as if it had been made only a few minutes 
before. It was the footprint of Buster Bear.

362
00:34:28,960 --> 00:34:34,000
Now Farmer Brown's boy didn't know 
that Buster Bear had come down  

363
00:34:34,000 --> 00:34:39,920
to the Green Forest to live. He never had 
heard of a Bear being in the Green Forest.

364
00:34:40,560 --> 00:34:45,840
And so he was so surprised that he 
had hard work to believe his own eyes,  

365
00:34:45,840 --> 00:34:52,880
and he had a queer feeling all over,—a little 
chilly feeling, although it was a warm day.  

366
00:34:53,920 --> 00:35:00,160
Somehow, he didn't feel like meeting Buster 
Bear. If he had had his terrible gun with him,  

367
00:35:00,160 --> 00:35:06,160
it might have been different. But he didn't, 
and so he suddenly made up his mind that he  

368
00:35:06,160 --> 00:35:12,560
didn't want to fish any more that day. He had a 
funny feeling, too, that he was being watched,  

369
00:35:12,560 --> 00:35:19,280
although he couldn't see any one. He 
was being watched. Little Joe Otter  

370
00:35:19,280 --> 00:35:25,200
and Buster Bear were watching him and taking 
the greatest care to keep out of his sight.

371
00:35:26,640 --> 00:35:31,920
All the way home through the Green Forest, 
Farmer Brown's boy kept looking behind him,  

372
00:35:32,640 --> 00:35:36,560
and he didn't draw a long breath until 
he reached the edge of the Green Forest.  

373
00:35:37,360 --> 00:35:40,240
He hadn't run, but he had wanted to.

374
00:35:42,360 --> 00:35:48,320
"Huh!" said Buster Bear to Little 
Joe Otter, "I believe he was afraid!"

375
00:35:49,680 --> 00:35:53,360
And Buster Bear was just exactly right.

376
00:35:55,120 --> 00:35:55,760
CHAPTER IX

377
00:36:05,360 --> 00:36:07,280
LITTLE JOE OTTER HAS GREAT NEWS

378
00:36:07,280 --> 00:36:07,680
TO TELL

379
00:36:08,960 --> 00:36:14,160
Little Joe Otter was fairly bursting with 
excitement. He could hardly contain himself.  

380
00:36:14,800 --> 00:36:20,400
He felt that he had the greatest news to tell 
since Peter Rabbit had first found the tracks  

381
00:36:20,400 --> 00:36:26,240
of Buster Bear in the Green Forest. He couldn't 
keep it to himself a minute longer than he had to.  

382
00:36:26,800 --> 00:36:32,880
So he hurried to the Smiling Pool, where he 
was sure he would find Billy Mink and Jerry  

383
00:36:32,880 --> 00:36:38,720
Muskrat and Grandfather Frog and Spotty 
the Turtle, and he hoped that perhaps  

384
00:36:38,720 --> 00:36:42,400
some of the little people who live in 
the Green Forest might be there too.  

385
00:36:43,280 --> 00:36:50,400
Sure enough, Peter Rabbit was there on one side 
of the Smiling Pool, making faces at Reddy Fox,  

386
00:36:50,400 --> 00:36:55,280
who was on the other side, which, of 
course, was not at all nice of Peter.  

387
00:36:56,800 --> 00:37:02,240
Mr. and Mrs. Redwing were there, and Blacky 
the Crow was sitting in the Big Hickory-tree.

388
00:37:03,520 --> 00:37:10,720
Little Joe Otter swam straight to the Big Rock 
and climbed up to the very highest part. He looked  

389
00:37:10,720 --> 00:37:16,640
so excited, and his eyes sparkled so, that every 
one knew right away that something had happened.

390
00:37:17,600 --> 00:37:21,440
"Hi!" cried Billy Mink. "Look at Little Joe Otter!  

391
00:37:21,440 --> 00:37:25,920
It must be that for once he has 
been smarter than Buster Bear."

392
00:37:27,280 --> 00:37:34,240
Little Joe made a good-natured face at Billy 
Mink and shook his head. "No, Billy," said he,  

393
00:37:34,240 --> 00:37:40,640
"you are wrong, altogether wrong. I don't 
believe anybody can be smarter than Buster Bear."

394
00:37:40,640 --> 00:37:42,320
Illus Reddy glared across 
the Smiling Pool at Peter.

395
00:37:42,320 --> 00:37:50,320
Reddy Fox rolled his lips back in an 
unpleasant grin. "Don't be too sure of that!"

396
00:37:50,320 --> 00:37:53,040
he snapped. "I'm not through with him yet."

397
00:37:54,000 --> 00:37:56,880
"Boaster! Boaster!" cried Peter Rabbit.

398
00:37:57,600 --> 00:38:04,480
Reddy glared across the Smiling Pool at Peter. 
"I'm not through with you either, Peter Rabbit!"  

399
00:38:04,480 --> 00:38:08,240
he snarled. "You'll find it 
out one of these fine days!"

400
00:38:09,280 --> 00:38:11,440
"Reddy, Reddy, smart and sly,

401
00:38:11,440 --> 00:38:13,680
Couldn't catch a buzzing fly!"

402
00:38:13,680 --> 00:38:14,560
taunted Peter.

403
00:38:16,280 --> 00:38:20,560
"Chug-a-rum!" said Grandfather Frog 
in his deepest, gruffest voice.  

404
00:38:21,280 --> 00:38:27,360
"We know all about that. What we want to know 
is what Little Joe Otter has got on his mind."

405
00:38:28,320 --> 00:38:31,840
"It's news—great news!" cried Little Joe.

406
00:38:32,720 --> 00:38:37,280
"We can tell better how great 
it is when we hear what it is,"  

407
00:38:37,280 --> 00:38:41,040
replied Grandfather Frog testily. "What is it?"

408
00:38:42,720 --> 00:38:48,720
Little Joe Otter looked around at all the eager 
faces watching him, and then in the slowest,  

409
00:38:48,720 --> 00:39:00,240
most provoking way, he drawled: "Farmer 
Brown's boy is afraid of Buster Bear."

410
00:39:00,240 --> 00:39:06,000
For a minute no one said a word. 
Then Blacky the Crow leaned down  

411
00:39:06,000 --> 00:39:11,840
from his perch in the Big Hickory-tree and 
looked very hard at Little Joe as he said:

412
00:39:12,880 --> 00:39:17,120
"I don't believe it. I don't believe a word of it.  

413
00:39:17,680 --> 00:39:23,120
Farmer Brown's boy isn't afraid of 
any one who lives in the Green Forest  

414
00:39:23,120 --> 00:39:30,080
or on the Green Meadows or in the Smiling Pool, 
and you know it. We are all afraid of him."

415
00:39:31,360 --> 00:39:37,920
Little Joe glared back at Blacky. "I don't care 
whether you believe it or not; it's true," he  

416
00:39:37,920 --> 00:39:44,400
retorted. Then he told how early that very morning 
he and Buster Bear had been fishing together in  

417
00:39:44,400 --> 00:39:50,240
the Laughing Brook, and how Farmer Brown's boy 
had been fishing there too, and hadn't caught a  

418
00:39:50,240 --> 00:39:56,560
single trout because they had all been caught or 
frightened before he got there. Then he told how  

419
00:39:56,560 --> 00:40:02,720
Farmer Brown's boy had found a footprint of Buster 
Bear in the soft mud, and how he had stopped  

420
00:40:02,720 --> 00:40:08,480
fishing right away and started for home, looking 
behind him with fear in his eyes all the way.

421
00:40:09,360 --> 00:40:16,160
"Now tell me that he isn't afraid!" concluded 
Little Joe. "For once he knows just how we feel  

422
00:40:16,160 --> 00:40:23,840
when he comes prowling around where we are. Isn't 
that great news? Now we'll get even with him!"

423
00:40:25,120 --> 00:40:30,400
"I'll believe it when I see it for 
myself!" snapped Blacky the Crow.

424
00:40:32,720 --> 00:40:33,520
CHAPTER X

425
00:40:37,760 --> 00:40:39,600
BUSTER BEAR BECOMES A HERO

426
00:40:40,800 --> 00:40:46,160
The news that Little Joe Otter told at the 
Smiling Pool,—how Farmer Brown's boy had  

427
00:40:46,160 --> 00:40:52,480
run away from Buster Bear without even seeing 
him,—soon spread all over the Green Meadows and  

428
00:40:52,480 --> 00:40:57,840
through the Green Forest, until every one 
who lives there knew about it. Of course,  

429
00:40:57,840 --> 00:41:03,920
Peter Rabbit helped spread it. Trust Peter for 
that! But everybody else helped too. You see,  

430
00:41:03,920 --> 00:41:10,480
they had all been afraid of Farmer Brown's boy for 
so long that they were tickled almost to pieces at  

431
00:41:10,480 --> 00:41:16,480
the very thought of having some one in the Green 
Forest who could make Farmer Brown's boy feel fear  

432
00:41:16,480 --> 00:41:23,440
as they had felt it. And so it was that Buster 
Bear became a hero right away to most of them.

433
00:41:24,800 --> 00:41:32,480
A few doubted Little Joe's story. One of them was 
Blacky the Crow. Another was Reddy Fox. Blacky  

434
00:41:32,480 --> 00:41:39,280
doubted because he knew Farmer Brown's boy so well 
that he couldn't imagine him afraid. Reddy doubted  

435
00:41:39,280 --> 00:41:46,000
because he didn't want to believe. You see, he 
was jealous of Buster Bear, and at the same time  

436
00:41:46,000 --> 00:41:52,080
he was afraid of him. So Reddy pretended not to 
believe a word of what Little Joe Otter had said,  

437
00:41:52,080 --> 00:41:58,720
and he agreed with Blacky that only by seeing 
Farmer Brown's boy afraid could he ever be made to  

438
00:41:58,720 --> 00:42:05,360
believe it. But nearly everybody else believed it, 
and there was great rejoicing. Most of them were  

439
00:42:05,360 --> 00:42:12,800
afraid of Buster, very much afraid of him, because 
he was so big and strong. But they were still more  

440
00:42:12,800 --> 00:42:19,520
afraid of Farmer Brown's boy, because they didn't 
know him or understand him, and because in the  

441
00:42:19,520 --> 00:42:25,600
past he had tried to catch some of them in traps 
and had hunted some of them with his terrible gun.

442
00:42:27,440 --> 00:42:33,680
So now they were very proud to think that one 
of their own number actually had frightened him,  

443
00:42:33,680 --> 00:42:40,640
and they began to look on Buster Bear as a real 
hero. They tried in ever so many ways to show  

444
00:42:40,640 --> 00:42:45,760
him how friendly they felt and went quite out 
of their way to do him favors. Whenever they  

445
00:42:45,760 --> 00:42:52,880
met one another, all they could talk about was 
the smartness and the greatness of Buster Bear.

446
00:42:54,240 --> 00:42:58,240
"Now I guess Farmer Brown's boy will 
keep away from the Green Forest,  

447
00:42:58,240 --> 00:43:02,800
and we won't have to be all the time 
watching out for him," said Bobby Coon,  

448
00:43:02,800 --> 00:43:07,840
as he washed his dinner in the Laughing Brook, 
for you know he is very neat and particular.

449
00:43:09,040 --> 00:43:13,200
"And he won't dare set any more 
traps for me," gloated Billy Mink.

450
00:43:14,160 --> 00:43:20,720
"Ah wish Brer Bear would go up to Farmer Brown's 
henhouse and scare Farmer Brown's boy so that  

451
00:43:20,720 --> 00:43:26,880
he would keep away from there. It would be a 
favor to me which Ah cert'nly would appreciate,"  

452
00:43:27,680 --> 00:43:30,320
said Unc' Billy Possum when he heard the news.

453
00:43:31,040 --> 00:43:35,840
"Let's all go together and tell Buster Bear 
how much obliged we are for what he has done,"  

454
00:43:36,400 --> 00:43:37,840
proposed Jerry Muskrat.

455
00:43:38,400 --> 00:43:42,720
"That's a splendid idea!" cried Little 
Joe Otter. "We'll do it right away."

456
00:43:42,720 --> 00:43:47,040
"Caw, caw caw!"  

457
00:43:47,040 --> 00:43:54,080
broke in Blacky the Crow. "I say, let's wait 
and see for ourselves if it is all true."

458
00:43:54,080 --> 00:44:00,080
"Of course it's true!" snapped Little Joe Otter. 
"Don't you believe I'm telling the truth?"

459
00:44:00,960 --> 00:44:07,520
"Certainly, certainly. Of course no one doubts 
your word," replied Blacky, with the utmost  

460
00:44:07,520 --> 00:44:14,880
politeness. "But you say yourself that Farmer 
Brown's boy didn't see Buster Bear, but only his  

461
00:44:14,880 --> 00:44:23,040
footprint. Perhaps he didn't know whose it was, 
and if he had he wouldn't have been afraid. Now  

462
00:44:23,600 --> 00:44:29,920
I've got a plan by which we can see for 
ourselves if he really is afraid of Buster Bear."

463
00:44:30,480 --> 00:44:33,440
"What is it?" asked Sammy Jay eagerly.

464
00:44:34,400 --> 00:44:42,320
Blacky the Crow shook his head and winked. "That's 
telling," said he. "I want to think it over.  

465
00:44:42,320 --> 00:44:46,720
If you meet me at the Big Hickory-tree 
at sun-up to-morrow morning,  

466
00:44:46,720 --> 00:44:52,080
and get everybody else to come that 
you can, perhaps I will tell you."

467
00:44:54,000 --> 00:44:54,720
CHAPTER XI

468
00:44:57,040 --> 00:44:59,120
BLACKY THE CROW TELLS HIS PLAN

469
00:45:00,320 --> 00:45:02,000
Blacky is a dreamer!

470
00:45:02,000 --> 00:45:04,320
Blacky is a schemer!

471
00:45:04,320 --> 00:45:05,680
His voice is strong;

472
00:45:05,680 --> 00:45:06,880
When things go wrong

473
00:45:07,520 --> 00:45:09,360
Blacky is a screamer!

474
00:45:10,560 --> 00:45:17,040
It's a fact. Blacky the Crow is forever 
dreaming and scheming and almost always  

475
00:45:17,040 --> 00:45:21,760
it is of mischief. He is one of the smartest 
and cleverest of all the little people of the  

476
00:45:21,760 --> 00:45:27,920
Green Meadows and the Green Forest, and all 
the others know it. Blacky likes excitement.  

477
00:45:27,920 --> 00:45:33,360
He wants something going on. The more 
exciting it is, the better he likes it.  

478
00:45:33,360 --> 00:45:38,480
Then he has a chance to use that harsh 
voice of his, and how he does use it!

479
00:45:39,360 --> 00:45:45,040
So now, as he sat in the top of the Big 
Hickory-tree beside the Smiling Pool and  

480
00:45:45,040 --> 00:45:49,200
looked down on all the little people 
gathered there, he was very happy.  

481
00:45:49,840 --> 00:45:56,080
In the first place he felt very important, and 
you know Blacky dearly loves to feel important.  

482
00:45:56,640 --> 00:46:02,080
They had all come at his invitation to listen 
to a plan for seeing for themselves if it were  

483
00:46:02,080 --> 00:46:05,680
really true that Farmer Brown's 
boy was afraid of Buster Bear.

484
00:46:06,320 --> 00:46:13,520
On the Big Rock in the Smiling Pool sat Little Joe 
Otter, Billy Mink, and Jerry Muskrat. On his big,  

485
00:46:13,520 --> 00:46:19,840
green lily-pad sat Grandfather Frog. On 
another lily-pad sat Spotty the Turtle.  

486
00:46:20,480 --> 00:46:26,240
On the bank on one side of the Smiling Pool 
were Peter Rabbit, Jumper the Hare, Danny  

487
00:46:26,240 --> 00:46:33,760
Meadow Mouse, Johnny Chuck, Jimmy Skunk, Unc' 
Billy Possum, Striped Chipmunk and Old Mr. Toad.  

488
00:46:34,560 --> 00:46:42,080
On the other side of the Smiling Pool were Reddy 
Fox, Digger the Badger, and Bobby Coon. In the Big  

489
00:46:42,080 --> 00:46:47,760
Hickory-tree were Chatterer the Red Squirrel, 
Happy Jack the Gray Squirrel, and Sammy Jay.

490
00:46:48,800 --> 00:46:52,320
Blacky waited until he was sure 
that no one else was coming.  

491
00:46:52,320 --> 00:46:59,120
Then he cleared his throat very loudly 
and began to speak. "Friends," said he.

492
00:47:00,160 --> 00:47:06,320
Everybody grinned, for Blacky has played so many 
sharp tricks that no one is really his friend  

493
00:47:06,320 --> 00:47:09,920
unless it is that other 
mischief-maker, Sammy Jay, who, you

494
00:47:09,920 --> 00:47:15,520
know, is Blacky's cousin. But no one 
said anything, and Blacky went on.

495
00:47:16,320 --> 00:47:23,200
"Little Joe Otter has told us how he saw Farmer 
Brown's boy hurry home when he found the footprint  

496
00:47:23,200 --> 00:47:29,280
of Buster Bear on the edge of the Laughing Brook, 
and how all the way he kept looking behind him,  

497
00:47:29,280 --> 00:47:36,720
as if he were afraid. Perhaps he was, and 
then again perhaps he wasn't. Perhaps he had  

498
00:47:36,720 --> 00:47:43,360
something else on his mind. You have made a hero 
of Buster Bear, because you believe Little Joe's  

499
00:47:43,360 --> 00:47:51,040
story. Now I don't say that I don't believe it, 
but I do say that I will be a lot more sure that  

500
00:47:51,040 --> 00:47:58,880
Farmer Brown's boy is afraid of Buster when I 
see him run away myself. Now here is my plan:

501
00:48:00,160 --> 00:48:06,720
"To-morrow morning, very early, Sammy Jay and 
I will make a great fuss near the edge of the  

502
00:48:06,720 --> 00:48:13,920
Green Forest. Farmer Brown's boy has a lot of 
curiosity, and he will be sure to come over  

503
00:48:13,920 --> 00:48:22,160
to see what it is all about. Then we will lead 
him to where Buster Bear is. If he runs away, I  

504
00:48:22,160 --> 00:48:27,280
will be the first to admit that Buster Bear is as 
great a hero as some of you seem to think he is.  

505
00:48:28,320 --> 00:48:32,960
It is a very simple plan, and if you 
will all hide where you can watch,  

506
00:48:32,960 --> 00:48:39,920
you will be able to see for yourselves if 
Little Joe Otter is right. Now what do you say?"

507
00:48:41,680 --> 00:48:46,800
Right away everybody began to talk at the 
same time. It was such a simple plan that  

508
00:48:46,800 --> 00:48:52,400
everybody agreed to it. And it promised to be 
so exciting that everybody promised to be there,  

509
00:48:52,400 --> 00:48:58,400
that is, everybody but Grandfather Frog and 
Spotty the Turtle, who didn't care to go so far  

510
00:48:58,400 --> 00:49:06,080
away from the Smiling Pool. So it was agreed that 
Blacky should try his plan the very next morning.

511
00:49:07,760 --> 00:49:08,640
CHAPTER XII

512
00:49:11,840 --> 00:49:13,760
FARMER BROWN'S BOY AND BUSTER

513
00:49:13,760 --> 00:49:16,320
BEAR GROW CURIOUS

514
00:49:16,320 --> 00:49:20,640
Ever since it was light enough to see at 
all, Blacky the Crow had been sitting in  

515
00:49:20,640 --> 00:49:26,160
the top of the tallest tree on the edge of the 
Green Forest nearest to Farmer Brown's house,  

516
00:49:26,720 --> 00:49:32,240
and never for an instant had he taken his 
eyes from Farmer Brown's back door. What was  

517
00:49:32,240 --> 00:49:39,600
he watching for? Why, for Farmer Brown's boy to 
come out on his way to milk the cows. Meanwhile,  

518
00:49:39,600 --> 00:49:45,040
Sammy Jay was slipping silently through the 
Green Forest, looking for Buster Bear, so that  

519
00:49:45,040 --> 00:49:50,480
when the time came he could let his cousin, 
Blacky the Crow, know just where Buster was.

520
00:49:51,200 --> 00:49:55,040
By and by the back door of 
Farmer Brown's house opened,  

521
00:49:55,040 --> 00:49:59,920
and out stepped Farmer Brown's boy. 
In each hand he carried a milk pail.  

522
00:50:00,800 --> 00:50:08,240
Right away Blacky began to scream at 
the top of his lungs. "Caw, caw, caw!"  

523
00:50:08,240 --> 00:50:16,480
shouted Blacky. "Caw, caw, caw!" And all the 
time he flew about among the trees near the  

524
00:50:16,480 --> 00:50:22,000
edge of the Green Forest as if so excited 
that he couldn't keep still. Farmer Brown's  

525
00:50:22,000 --> 00:50:27,200
boy looked over there as if he wondered what 
all that fuss was about, as indeed he did,  

526
00:50:27,200 --> 00:50:32,960
but he didn't start to go over and see. 
No, Sir, he started straight for the barn.

527
00:50:34,160 --> 00:50:40,880
Blacky didn't know what to make of it. You see, 
smart as he is and shrewd as he is, Blacky doesn't  

528
00:50:40,880 --> 00:50:47,120
know anything about the meaning of duty, for he 
never has to work excepting to get enough to eat.  

529
00:50:47,120 --> 00:50:52,000
So, when Farmer Brown's boy started for 
the barn instead of for the Green Forest,  

530
00:50:52,000 --> 00:50:53,840
Blacky didn't know what to make of it.

531
00:50:54,400 --> 00:51:00,640
He screamed harder and louder than ever, until his 
voice grew so hoarse he couldn't scream any more,  

532
00:51:00,640 --> 00:51:04,400
but Farmer Brown's boy kept right on to the barn.

533
00:51:04,400 --> 00:51:08,160
"I'd like to know what you're 
making such a fuss about, Mr. Crow,  

534
00:51:08,160 --> 00:51:12,000
but I've got to feed the cows 
and milk them first," said he.

535
00:51:12,720 --> 00:51:17,680
Now all this time the other little people 
of the Green Forest and the Green Meadows  

536
00:51:17,680 --> 00:51:22,240
had been hiding where they could see all 
that went on. When Farmer Brown's boy  

537
00:51:22,240 --> 00:51:26,880
disappeared in the barn, Chatterer the 
Red Squirrel snickered right out loud.  

538
00:51:28,880 --> 00:51:34,320
"Ha, ha, ha! This is a great plan of yours, 
Blacky! Ha, ha, ha!" he shouted. Blacky  

539
00:51:34,320 --> 00:51:39,760
couldn't find a word to say. He just hung his 
head, which is something Blacky seldom does.

540
00:51:40,560 --> 00:51:44,720
"Perhaps if we wait until he comes 
out again, he will come over here,"  

541
00:51:44,720 --> 00:51:51,680
said Sammy Jay, who had joined Blacky. So it was 
decided to wait. It seemed as if Farmer Brown's  

542
00:51:51,680 --> 00:51:58,320
boy never would come out, but at last he did. 
Blacky and Sammy Jay at once began to scream  

543
00:51:58,320 --> 00:52:03,840
and make all the fuss they could. Farmer Brown's 
boy took the two pails of milk into the house,  

544
00:52:04,480 --> 00:52:08,000
then out he came and started 
straight for the Green Forest.  

545
00:52:08,000 --> 00:52:11,920
He was so curious to know what it all 
meant that he couldn't wait another minute.

546
00:52:13,360 --> 00:52:16,960
Now there was some one else with 
a great deal of curiosity also.  

547
00:52:17,600 --> 00:52:21,680
He had heard the screaming of 
Blacky the Crow and Sammy Jay,  

548
00:52:21,680 --> 00:52:23,440
and he had listened until he couldn't stand 
it another minute. He just had to know what  

549
00:52:23,440 --> 00:52:29,520
it was all about. So at the same time Farmer 
Brown's boy started for the Green Forest,  

550
00:52:29,520 --> 00:52:35,200
this other listener started towards the place 
where Blacky and Sammy were making such a racket.  

551
00:52:35,760 --> 00:52:41,440
He walked very softly so as not to 
make a sound. It was Buster Bear.

552
00:52:43,280 --> 00:52:50,240
CHAPTER XIII

553
00:52:53,600 --> 00:52:55,520
FARMER BROWN'S BOY AND BUSTER

554
00:52:55,520 --> 00:52:56,400
BEAR MEET

555
00:52:57,920 --> 00:53:00,000
If you should meet with Buster Bear

556
00:53:00,000 --> 00:53:01,360
While walking through the wood,

557
00:53:02,000 --> 00:53:04,320
What would you do? Now tell me true,

558
00:53:04,960 --> 00:53:06,880
I'd run the best I could.

559
00:53:08,000 --> 00:53:11,600
That is what Farmer Brown's boy 
did when he met Buster Bear,  

560
00:53:11,600 --> 00:53:16,480
and a lot of the little people of the Green 
Forest and some from the Green Meadows saw him.

561
00:53:17,280 --> 00:53:22,400
When Farmer Brown's boy came hurrying home from 
the Laughing Brook without any fish one day  

562
00:53:22,400 --> 00:53:27,040
and told about the great footprint he had 
seen in a muddy place on the bank deep  

563
00:53:27,040 --> 00:53:32,240
in the Green Forest, and had said his was 
sure that it was the footprint of a Bear,  

564
00:53:32,240 --> 00:53:37,600
he had been laughed at. Farmer 
Brown had laughed and laughed.

565
00:53:37,600 --> 00:53:43,280
"Why," said he, "there hasn't been a Bear in the 
Green Forest for years and years and years, not  

566
00:53:43,280 --> 00:53:49,680
since my own grandfather was a little boy, and 
that, you know, was a long, long, long time ago.  

567
00:53:50,320 --> 00:53:56,160
If you want to find Mr. Bear, you will have to 
go to the Great Woods. I don't know who made  

568
00:53:56,160 --> 00:54:01,600
that footprint, but it certainly couldn't have 
been a Bear. I think you must have imagined it."

569
00:54:02,960 --> 00:54:08,640
Then he had laughed some more, all of which 
goes to show how easy it is to be mistaken,  

570
00:54:08,640 --> 00:54:13,200
and how foolish it is to laugh at 
things you really don't know about.

571
00:54:14,000 --> 00:54:20,640
Buster Bear had come to live in the Green Forest, 
and Farmer Brown's boy had seen his footprint.  

572
00:54:21,200 --> 00:54:25,520
But Farmer Brown laughed so much 
and made fun of him so much,  

573
00:54:25,520 --> 00:54:30,000
that at last his boy began to think that 
he must have been mistaken after all.  

574
00:54:30,560 --> 00:54:35,680
So when he heard Blacky the Crow and Sammy Jay 
making a great fuss near the edge of the Green  

575
00:54:35,680 --> 00:54:41,680
Forest, he never once thought of Buster Bear, 
as he started over to see what was going on.

576
00:54:42,640 --> 00:54:48,400
When Blacky and Sammy saw him coming, they 
moved a little farther in to the Green Forest,  

577
00:54:48,400 --> 00:54:55,040
still screaming in the most excited way. They felt 
sure that Farmer Brown's boy would follow them,  

578
00:54:55,040 --> 00:54:59,120
and they meant to lead him to where 
Sammy had seen Buster Bear that morning.  

579
00:54:59,920 --> 00:55:02,560
Then they would find out for sure if what

580
00:55:02,560 --> 00:55:09,200
Little Joe Otter had said was true,—that Farmer 
Brown's boy really was afraid of Buster Bear.

581
00:55:10,080 --> 00:55:17,440
Now all around, behind trees and stumps, and under 
thick branches, and even in tree tops, were other  

582
00:55:17,440 --> 00:55:24,800
little people watching with round, wide-open eyes 
to see what would happen. It was very exciting,  

583
00:55:24,800 --> 00:55:30,560
the most exciting thing they could remember. You 
see, they had come to believe that Farmer Brown's  

584
00:55:30,560 --> 00:55:36,560
boy wasn't afraid of anybody or anything, and 
as most of them were very much afraid of him,  

585
00:55:36,560 --> 00:55:42,080
they had hard work to believe that he would 
really be afraid of even such a great, big,  

586
00:55:42,080 --> 00:55:47,840
strong fellow as Buster Bear. Every one 
was so busy watching Farmer Brown's boy  

587
00:55:48,400 --> 00:55:51,840
that no one saw Buster coming 
from the other direction.

588
00:55:52,720 --> 00:56:00,320
You see, Buster walked very softly. Big as he is, 
he can walk without making the teeniest, weeniest  

589
00:56:00,320 --> 00:56:07,760
sound. And that is how it happened that no one saw 
him or heard him until just as Farmer Brown's boy  

590
00:56:07,760 --> 00:56:15,120
stepped out from behind one side of a thick little 
hemlock-tree, Buster Bear stepped out from behind  

591
00:56:15,120 --> 00:56:24,000
the other side of that same little tree, and there 
they were face to face! Then everybody held their  

592
00:56:24,000 --> 00:56:30,480
breath, even Blacky the Crow and Sammy Jay. 
For just a little minute it was so still there  

593
00:56:30,480 --> 00:56:36,240
in the Green Forest that not the least little 
sound could be heard. What was going to happen?

594
00:56:38,240 --> 00:56:39,200
CHAPTER XIV

595
00:56:42,720 --> 00:56:44,240
A SURPRISING THING HAPPENS

596
00:56:45,520 --> 00:56:51,760
Blacky the Crow and Sammy Jay, looking down from 
the top of a tall tree, held their breath. Happy  

597
00:56:51,760 --> 00:56:57,360
Jack the Gray Squirrel and his cousin, Chatterer 
the Red Squirrel, looking down from another tree,  

598
00:56:57,360 --> 00:57:04,240
held their breath. Unc' Billy Possum, sticking 
his head out from a hollow tree, held his breath.  

599
00:57:05,120 --> 00:57:09,520
Bobby Coon, looking through a hole in 
a hollow stump in which he was hiding,  

600
00:57:09,520 --> 00:57:18,560
held his breath. Reddy Fox, lying flat down behind 
a heap of brush, held his breath. Peter Rabbit,  

601
00:57:18,560 --> 00:57:26,000
sitting bolt upright under a thick hemlock branch, 
with eyes and ears wide open, held his breath.  

602
00:57:26,000 --> 00:57:31,840
And all the other little people who happened 
to be where they could see did the same thing.

603
00:57:31,840 --> 00:57:36,000
You see, it was the most exciting 
moment ever was in the Green Forest.  

604
00:57:36,640 --> 00:57:40,000
Farmer Brown's boy had just 
stepped out from behind one side  

605
00:57:40,000 --> 00:57:45,520
of a little hemlock-tree and Buster Bear had 
just stepped out from behind the opposite side  

606
00:57:45,520 --> 00:57:51,840
of the little hemlock-tree and neither had 
known that the other was anywhere near. For  

607
00:57:51,840 --> 00:57:58,000
a whole minute they stood there face to face, 
gazing into each other's eyes, while everybody  

608
00:57:58,000 --> 00:58:03,840
watched and waited, and it seemed as if the 
whole Green Forest was holding its breath.

609
00:58:04,560 --> 00:58:12,960
Then something happened. Yes, Sir, something 
happened. Farmer Brown's boy opened his mouth  

610
00:58:12,960 --> 00:58:20,880
and yelled! It was such a sudden yell and such 
a loud yell that it startled Chatterer so that  

611
00:58:20,880 --> 00:58:27,360
he nearly fell from his place in the tree, and it 
made Reddy Fox jump to his feet ready to run. And  

612
00:58:27,360 --> 00:58:35,600
that yell was a yell of fright. There was no doubt 
about it, for with the yell Farmer Brown's boy  

613
00:58:35,600 --> 00:58:42,800
turned and ran for home, as no one ever had seen 
him run before. He ran just as Peter Rabbit runs  

614
00:58:42,800 --> 00:58:48,240
when he has got to reach the dear Old Briar-patch 
before Reddy Fox can catch him, which, you know,  

615
00:58:48,240 --> 00:58:54,560
is as fast as he can run. Once he stumbled and 
fell, but he scrambled to his feet in a twinkling,  

616
00:58:54,560 --> 00:58:59,200
and away he went without once turning his 
head to see if Buster Bear was after him.  

617
00:58:59,920 --> 00:59:04,240
There wasn't any doubt that he 
was afraid, very much afraid.

618
00:59:04,960 --> 00:59:09,600
Everybody leaned forward to watch him. 
"What did I tell you? Didn't I say that  

619
00:59:09,600 --> 00:59:14,400
he was afraid of Buster Bear?" cried Little 
Joe Otter, dancing about with excitement.

620
00:59:15,040 --> 00:59:25,280
"You were right, Little Joe! I'm sorry that 
I doubted it. See him go! Caw, caw, caw!"  

621
00:59:25,280 --> 00:59:26,640
shrieked Blacky the Crow.

622
00:59:27,680 --> 00:59:33,840
For a minute or two everybody forgot about Buster 
Bear. Then there was a great crash which made  

623
00:59:33,840 --> 00:59:41,360
everybody turn to look the other way. What do you 
think they saw? Why, Buster Bear was running away  

624
00:59:41,360 --> 00:59:47,360
too, and he was running twice as fast as Farmer 
Brown's boy! He bumped into trees and crashed  

625
00:59:47,360 --> 00:59:54,560
through bushes and jumped over logs, and in almost 
no time at all he was out of sight. Altogether it  

626
00:59:54,560 --> 00:59:59,840
was the most surprising thing that the little 
people of the Green Forest ever had seen.

627
00:59:59,840 --> 01:00:00,320
Illus Buster Bear was running away, too

628
01:00:00,320 --> 01:00:06,160
Sammy Jay looked at Blacky the Crow, and Blacky 
looked at Chatterer, and Chatterer looked at Happy  

629
01:00:06,160 --> 01:00:12,480
Jack, and Happy Jack looked at Peter Rabbit, and 
Peter looked at Unc' Billy Possum, and Unc' Billy  

630
01:00:13,200 --> 01:00:18,960
looked at Bobby Coon, and Bobby looked at 
Johnny Chuck, and Johnny looked at Reddy Fox,  

631
01:00:18,960 --> 01:00:24,640
and Reddy looked at Jimmy Skunk, and Jimmy 
looked at Billy Mink, and Billy looked at Little  

632
01:00:24,640 --> 01:00:33,360
Joe Otter, and for a minute nobody could say a 
word. Then Little Joe gave a funny little gasp.

633
01:00:33,920 --> 01:00:36,560
"Why, why-e-e!" said he,  

634
01:00:38,080 --> 01:00:44,720
"I believe Buster Bear is afraid too!" 
Unc' Billy Possum chuckled. "Ah believe  

635
01:00:44,720 --> 01:00:51,760
yo' are right again, Brer Otter," said he. "It 
cert'nly does look so. If Brer Bear isn't scared,  

636
01:00:51,760 --> 01:00:57,600
he must have remembered something impo'tant and 
has gone to attend to it in a powerful hurry."

637
01:00:58,720 --> 01:01:01,280
Then everybody began to laugh.

638
01:01:02,800 --> 01:01:03,760
CHAPTER XV

639
01:01:06,080 --> 01:01:08,080
BUSTER BEAR IS A FALLEN HERO

640
01:01:09,360 --> 01:01:16,000
A fallen hero is some one to whom every one has 
looked up as very brave and then proves to be less  

641
01:01:16,000 --> 01:01:23,040
brave than he was supposed to be. That was the way 
with Buster Bear. When Little Joe Otter had told  

642
01:01:23,040 --> 01:01:30,080
how Farmer Brown's boy had been afraid at the mere 
sight of one of Buster Bear's big footprints, they  

643
01:01:30,080 --> 01:01:37,200
had at once made a hero of Buster. At least some 
of them had. As this was the first time, the very  

644
01:01:37,200 --> 01:01:42,800
first time, that they had ever known any one who 
lives in the Green Forest to make Farmer Brown's  

645
01:01:42,800 --> 01:01:49,360
boy run away, they looked on Buster Bear with a 
great deal of respect and were very proud of him.

646
01:01:50,080 --> 01:01:55,040
But now they had seen Buster Bear and 
Farmer Brown's boy meet face to face;  

647
01:01:55,600 --> 01:02:01,520
and while it was true that Farmer Brown's boy had 
run away as fast as ever he could, it was also  

648
01:02:01,520 --> 01:02:08,640
true that Buster Bear had done the same thing. 
He had run even faster than Farmer Brown's boy,  

649
01:02:08,640 --> 01:02:14,720
and had hidden in the most lonely place he could 
find in the very deepest part of the Green Forest.  

650
01:02:15,520 --> 01:02:22,480
It was hard to believe, but it was true. And right 
away everybody lost a great deal of the respect  

651
01:02:22,480 --> 01:02:29,680
for Buster which they had felt. It is always that 
way. They began to say unkind things about him.  

652
01:02:29,680 --> 01:02:32,720
They said them among themselves, and some of them  

653
01:02:32,720 --> 01:02:37,280
even said them to Buster when they met him, 
or said them so that he would hear them.

654
01:02:38,080 --> 01:02:42,800
Of course Blacky the Crow and Sammy 
Jay, who, because they can fly,  

655
01:02:42,800 --> 01:02:47,840
have nothing to fear from Buster, and who always 
delight in making other people uncomfortable,  

656
01:02:48,640 --> 01:02:53,360
never let a chance go by to tell Buster 
and everybody else within hearing  

657
01:02:53,360 --> 01:02:58,320
what they thought of him. They delighted 
in flying about through the Green Forest  

658
01:02:58,320 --> 01:03:04,320
until they had found Buster Bear and then from 
the safety of the tree tops screaming at him.

659
01:03:05,040 --> 01:03:07,680
"Buster Bear is big and strong;

660
01:03:07,680 --> 01:03:10,960
His teeth are big; his claws are long;

661
01:03:10,960 --> 01:03:13,280
In spite of these he runs away

662
01:03:13,280 --> 01:03:15,840
And hides himself the livelong day!"

663
01:03:17,680 --> 01:03:21,200
A dozen times a day Buster 
would hear them screaming this.  

664
01:03:21,200 --> 01:03:27,520
He would grind his teeth and glare up at them, but 
that was all he could do. He couldn't get at them.

665
01:03:27,520 --> 01:03:33,840
He just had to stand it and do nothing. But when 
impudent little Chatterer the Red Squirrel shouted  

666
01:03:33,840 --> 01:03:41,120
the same thing from a place just out of reach in a 
big pine-tree, Buster could stand it no longer. He  

667
01:03:41,120 --> 01:03:47,760
gave a deep, angry growl that made little shivers 
run over Chatterer, and then suddenly he started  

668
01:03:47,760 --> 01:03:53,600
up that tree after Chatterer. With a frightened 
little shriek Chatterer scampered to the top of  

669
01:03:53,600 --> 01:04:00,320
the tree. He hadn't known that Buster could climb. 
But Buster is a splendid climber, especially when  

670
01:04:00,320 --> 01:04:08,000
the tree is big and stout as this one was, and 
now he went up after Chatterer, growling angrily.

671
01:04:09,040 --> 01:04:15,440
How Chatterer did wish that he had kept his 
tongue still! He ran to the very top of the tree,  

672
01:04:15,440 --> 01:04:19,440
so frightened that his teeth chattered, 
and when he looked down and saw Buster's  

673
01:04:19,440 --> 01:04:26,080
great mouth coming nearer and nearer, he nearly 
tumbled down with terror. The worst of it was  

674
01:04:26,080 --> 01:04:29,360
there wasn't another tree near 
enough for him to jump to.  

675
01:04:30,080 --> 01:04:36,320
He was in trouble this time, was Chatterer, 
sure enough! And there was no one to help him.

676
01:04:37,920 --> 01:04:39,840
CHAPTER XVI

677
01:04:42,160 --> 01:04:44,320
CHATTERER THE RED SQUIRREL JUMPS

678
01:04:44,320 --> 01:04:45,120
FOR HIS LIFE

679
01:04:46,000 --> 01:04:51,120
It isn't very often that Chatterer the Red 
Squirrel knows fear. That is one reason that  

680
01:04:51,120 --> 01:04:57,040
he is so often impudent and saucy. But once in 
a while a great fear takes possession of him,  

681
01:04:57,040 --> 01:05:00,960
as when he knows that Shadow 
the Weasel is looking for him.

682
01:05:00,960 --> 01:05:04,800
You see, he knows that Shadow 
can go wherever he can go.  

683
01:05:05,680 --> 01:05:09,680
There are very few of the little people of 
the Green Forest and the Green Meadows who  

684
01:05:09,680 --> 01:05:15,920
do not know fear at some time or other, but 
it comes to Chatterer as seldom as to any one,  

685
01:05:15,920 --> 01:05:21,920
because he is very sure of himself and his 
ability to hide or run away from danger.

686
01:05:21,920 --> 01:05:27,920
But now as he clung to a little branch near 
the top of a tall pine-tree in the Green Forest  

687
01:05:27,920 --> 01:05:34,400
and looked down at the big sharp teeth of Buster 
Bear drawing nearer and nearer, and listened to  

688
01:05:34,400 --> 01:05:41,680
the deep, angry growls that made his hair stand 
on end, Chatterer was too frightened to think. If  

689
01:05:41,680 --> 01:05:47,680
only he had kept his tongue still instead of 
saying hateful things to Buster Bear! If only  

690
01:05:47,680 --> 01:05:53,840
he had known that Buster could climb a tree! If 
only he had chosen a tree near enough to other  

691
01:05:53,840 --> 01:06:00,640
trees for him to jump across! But he had said 
hateful things, he had chosen to sit in a tree  

692
01:06:00,640 --> 01:06:07,920
which stood quite by itself, and Buster Bear could 
climb! Chatterer was in the worst kind of trouble,  

693
01:06:07,920 --> 01:06:13,760
and there was no one to blame but himself. That is 
usually the case with those who get into trouble.

694
01:06:15,040 --> 01:06:20,160
Nearer and nearer came Buster Bear, and 
deeper and angrier sounded his voice.

695
01:06:21,120 --> 01:06:26,160
Chatterer gave a little frightened gasp 
and looked this way and looked that way.

696
01:06:27,360 --> 01:06:32,800
What should he do? What could he do! The 
ground seemed a terrible distance below.  

697
01:06:33,440 --> 01:06:37,760
If only he had wings like 
Sammy Jay! But he hadn't.

698
01:06:40,360 --> 01:06:47,200
"Gr-r-r-r!" growled Buster Bear. "I'll teach 
you manners! I'll teach you to treat your  

699
01:06:47,200 --> 01:06:53,480
betters with respect! I'll swallow you 
whole, that's what I'll do. Gr-r-r-r!"

700
01:06:55,360 --> 01:06:57,920
"Oh!" cried Chatterer.

701
01:06:58,560 --> 01:07:05,040
"Gr-r-r-r! I'll eat you all 
up to the last hair on your  

702
01:07:05,040 --> 01:07:08,640
tail!" growled Buster, scrambling a little nearer.

703
01:07:08,640 --> 01:07:15,280
"Oh! Oh!" cried Chatterer, and ran out to the 
very tip of the little branch to which he had  

704
01:07:15,280 --> 01:07:21,600
been clinging. Now if Chatterer had only known 
it, Buster Bear couldn't reach him way up there,  

705
01:07:21,600 --> 01:07:27,360
because the tree was too small at the top for such 
a big fellow as Buster. But Chatterer didn't think  

706
01:07:27,360 --> 01:07:34,640
of that. He gave one more frightened look down at 
those big teeth, then he shut his eyes and jumped—

707
01:07:35,200 --> 01:07:37,840
jumped straight out for the far-away ground.

708
01:07:38,880 --> 01:07:44,960
It was a long, long, long way down to the 
ground, and it certainly looked as if such a  

709
01:07:44,960 --> 01:07:51,360
little fellow as Chatterer must be killed. But 
Chatterer had learned from Old Mother Nature  

710
01:07:51,360 --> 01:07:55,680
that she had given him certain things 
to help him at just such times,  

711
01:07:55,680 --> 01:08:00,880
and one of them is the power to spread 
himself very flat. He did it now.

712
01:08:01,440 --> 01:08:07,360
He spread his arms and legs out just as far as he 
could, and that kept him from falling as fast and  

713
01:08:07,360 --> 01:08:13,760
as hard as he otherwise would have done, because 
being spread out so flat that way, the air held  

714
01:08:13,760 --> 01:08:20,240
him up a little. And then there was his tail, that 
funny little tail he is so fond of jerking when he  

715
01:08:20,240 --> 01:08:27,120
scolds. This helped him too. It helped him keep 
his balance and keep from turning over and over.

716
01:08:28,400 --> 01:08:35,840
Down, down, down he sailed and landed on his 
feet. Of course, he hit the ground pretty hard,  

717
01:08:35,840 --> 01:08:41,120
and for just a second he quite lost his 
breath. But it was only for a second,  

718
01:08:41,120 --> 01:08:45,200
and then he was scurrying off as 
fast as a frightened Squirrel could.

719
01:08:46,160 --> 01:08:48,720
Buster Bear watched him and grinned.

720
01:08:49,520 --> 01:08:52,640
"I didn't catch him that time," he growled,  

721
01:08:53,200 --> 01:08:57,840
"but I guess I gave him a good 
fright and taught him a lesson."

722
01:09:00,320 --> 01:09:07,360
CHAPTER XVII

723
01:09:12,160 --> 01:09:14,480
BUSTER BEAR GOES BERRYING

724
01:09:16,400 --> 01:09:21,440
Buster Bear is a great hand to talk to himself 
when he thinks no one is around to overhear.  

725
01:09:22,320 --> 01:09:26,880
It's a habit. However, it isn't a bad 
habit unless it is carried too far.  

726
01:09:27,600 --> 01:09:34,640
Any habit becomes bad, if it is carried too 
far. Suppose you had a secret, a real secret,  

727
01:09:34,640 --> 01:09:38,480
something that nobody else knew and that 
you didn't want anybody else to know.

728
01:09:39,280 --> 01:09:41,920
And suppose you had the 
habit of talking to yourself.  

729
01:09:42,640 --> 01:09:49,360
You might, without thinking, you know, tell that 
secret out loud to yourself, and some one might,  

730
01:09:49,360 --> 01:09:53,840
just might happen to overhear! 
Then there wouldn't be any secret.  

731
01:09:54,720 --> 01:10:02,000
That is the way that a habit which isn't bad in 
itself can become bad when it is carried too far.

732
01:10:02,000 --> 01:10:07,200
Now Buster Bear had lived by himself in 
the Great Woods so long that this habit  

733
01:10:07,200 --> 01:10:12,880
of talking to himself had grown and grown. 
He did it just to keep from being lonesome.  

734
01:10:13,600 --> 01:10:18,480
Of course, when he came down to the Green 
Forest to live, he brought all his habits  

735
01:10:18,480 --> 01:10:24,160
with him. That is one thing about habits,—you 
always take them with you wherever you go.  

736
01:10:25,040 --> 01:10:29,680
So Buster brought this habit of talking 
to himself down to the Green Forest,  

737
01:10:29,680 --> 01:10:32,960
where he had many more neighbors 
than he had in the Great Woods.

738
01:10:34,480 --> 01:10:41,360
"Let me see, let me see, what 
is there to tempt my appetite?"  

739
01:10:41,360 --> 01:10:49,440
said Buster in his deep, grumbly-rumbly voice. 
"I find my appetite isn't what it ought to be.  

740
01:10:50,240 --> 01:10:59,200
I need a change. Yes, Sir, I need a change. There 
is something I ought to have at this time of year,  

741
01:10:59,200 --> 01:11:07,000
and I haven't got it. There is something 
that I used to have and don't have now. Ha!  

742
01:11:08,880 --> 01:11:19,440
I know! I need some fresh fruit. That's 
it—fresh fruit! It must be about berry time now,  

743
01:11:19,440 --> 01:11:27,120
and I'd forgotten all about it. My, my, 
my, how good some berries would taste!  

744
01:11:27,840 --> 01:11:34,360
Now if I were back up there in the Great 
Woods I could have all I could eat. Um-m-m-m!  

745
01:11:36,000 --> 01:11:39,120
Makes my mouth water just to think of it.

746
01:11:39,840 --> 01:11:44,640
There ought to be some up in the Old 
Pasture. There ought to be a lot of  

747
01:11:44,640 --> 01:11:50,640
'em up there. If I wasn't afraid that 
some one would see me, I'd go up there."

748
01:11:52,240 --> 01:12:00,320
Buster sighed. Then he sighed again. The 
more he thought about those berries he felt  

749
01:12:00,320 --> 01:12:06,880
sure were growing in the Old Pasture, the 
more he wanted some. It seemed to him that  

750
01:12:06,880 --> 01:12:13,680
never in all his life had he wanted berries 
as he did now. He wandered about uneasily.  

751
01:12:14,800 --> 01:12:19,200
He was hungry—hungry for berries and nothing else.

752
01:12:20,400 --> 01:12:23,600
By and by he began talking to himself again.

753
01:12:24,720 --> 01:12:31,120
"If I wasn't afraid of being seen, I'd go 
up to the Old Pasture this very minute.

754
01:12:32,000 --> 01:12:38,320
Seems as if I could taste those berries." 
He licked his lips hungrily as he spoke.

755
01:12:38,320 --> 01:12:44,720
Then his face brightened. "I know what 
I'll do! I'll go up there at the very  

756
01:12:44,720 --> 01:12:51,520
first peep of day to-morrow. I can eat all 
I want and get back to the Green Forest  

757
01:12:51,520 --> 01:12:58,240
before there is any danger that Farmer Brown's 
boy or any one else I'm afraid of will see me.  

758
01:12:59,040 --> 01:13:06,160
That's just what I'll do. My, I wish 
to-morrow morning would hurry up and come."

759
01:13:07,600 --> 01:13:14,720
Now though Buster didn't know it, some one 
had been listening, and that some one was  

