01:16:30,640 --> 01:16:34,160
You see, Farmer Brown's boy was 
just beginning to understand  

794
01:16:34,160 --> 01:16:38,400
something that Peter Rabbit and the 
other little people of the Green Meadows  

795
01:16:38,400 --> 01:16:43,680
and the Green Forest learned almost as soon as 
they learned to walk,—that if you don't want to

796
01:16:43,680 --> 01:16:50,320
be seen, you mustn't be heard. So he didn't 
whistle as he felt like doing, and he tried not to  

797
01:16:50,320 --> 01:16:55,760
make a bit of noise as he followed an old cow-path 
towards a place where he knew the berries grew  

798
01:16:55,760 --> 01:17:02,560
thick and oh, so big, and all the time he kept 
his eyes wide open, and he kept his ears open too.

799
01:17:03,760 --> 01:17:10,960
That is how he happened to hear a little cry, a 
very faint little cry. If he had been whistling,  

800
01:17:10,960 --> 01:17:16,560
he wouldn't have heard it at all. He stopped 
to listen. He never had heard a cry just like  

801
01:17:16,560 --> 01:17:23,040
it before. At first he couldn't make out just what 
it was or where it came from. But one thing he was  

802
01:17:23,040 --> 01:17:31,680
sure of, and that was that it was a cry of fright. 
He stood perfectly still and listened with all his  

803
01:17:31,680 --> 01:17:42,560
might. There it was again—"Help! Help! Help"—and 
it was very faint and sounded terribly frightened.  

804
01:17:43,440 --> 01:17:49,920
He waited a minute or two, but heard nothing more. 
Then he put down his pail and began a hurried look  

805
01:17:49,920 --> 01:17:55,200
here, there, and everywhere. He was sure that 
it had come from somewhere on the ground,  

806
01:17:55,200 --> 01:18:01,600
so he peered behind bushes and peeped behind 
logs and stones, and then just as he had about  

