861
01:23:47,120 --> 01:23:49,200
BUSTER BEAR CARRIES OFF THE PAIL

862
01:23:49,200 --> 01:23:50,560
OF FARMER BROWN'S BOY

863
01:23:51,760 --> 01:23:58,400
The question is, did Buster Bear steal 
Farmer Brown's boy's pail? To steal is  

864
01:23:58,400 --> 01:24:03,360
to take something which belongs to some 
one else. There is no doubt that he stole  

865
01:24:03,360 --> 01:24:07,520
the berries that were in the pail when he 
found it, for he deliberately ate them.

866
01:24:08,160 --> 01:24:14,080
He knew well enough that some one must have picked 
them—for whoever heard of blueberries growing in  

867
01:24:14,080 --> 01:24:22,640
tin pails? So there is no doubt that when Buster 
took them, he stole them. But with the pail it was  

868
01:24:22,640 --> 01:24:29,840
different. He took the pail, but he didn't mean to 
take it. In fact, he didn't want that pail at all.

869
01:24:31,840 --> 01:24:39,760
You see it was this way: When Buster found that 
big tin pail brimming full of delicious berries  

870
01:24:39,760 --> 01:24:46,080
in the shade of that big bush in the Old Pasture, 
he didn't stop to think whether or not he had a  

871
01:24:46,080 --> 01:24:52,640
right to them. Buster is so fond of berries that 
from the very second that his greedy little eyes  

872
01:24:52,640 --> 01:24:58,560
saw that pailful, he forgot everything but 
the feast that was waiting for him right  

873
01:24:58,560 --> 01:25:04,880
under his very nose. He didn't think anything 
about the right or wrong of helping himself.  

874
01:25:05,840 --> 01:25:12,080
There before him were more berries than he had 
ever seen together at one time in all his life,  

875
01:25:12,080 --> 01:25:18,000
and all he had to do was to eat and eat 
and eat. And that is just what he did do.  

876
01:25:19,520 --> 01:25:25,760
Of course he upset the pail, but he didn't mind a 
little thing like that. When he had gobbled up all  

877
01:25:25,760 --> 01:25:30,960
the berries that rolled out, he thrust his nose 
into the pail to get all that were left in it.  

878
01:25:31,680 --> 01:25:38,800
Just then he heard a little noise, as if some 
one were coming. He threw up his head to listen,  

879
01:25:39,440 --> 01:25:42,720
and somehow, he never did know just how,  

880
01:25:43,520 --> 01:25:48,560
the handle of the pail slipped back 
over his ears and caught there.

881
01:25:49,440 --> 01:25:56,400
This was bad enough, but to make matters worse, 
just at that very minute he heard a shrill,  

882
01:25:56,400 --> 01:26:04,160
angry voice shout, "Hi, there! Get out of there!" 
He didn't need to be told whose voice that was.  

883
01:26:04,720 --> 01:26:11,200
It was the voice of Farmer Brown's boy. Right 
then and there Buster Bear nearly had a fit.  

884
01:26:11,200 --> 01:26:16,560
There was that awful pail fast over his head 
so that he couldn't see a thing. Of course,  

885
01:26:16,560 --> 01:26:21,840
that meant that he couldn't run away, which was 
the thing of all things he most wanted to do,  

886
01:26:21,840 --> 01:26:28,720
for big as he is and strong as he is, Buster is 
very shy and bashful when human beings are around.

887
01:26:29,600 --> 01:26:35,840
He growled and whined and squealed. He 
tried to back out of the pail and couldn't.  

888
01:26:36,400 --> 01:26:41,520
He tried to shake it off and couldn't. 
He tried to pull it off, but somehow

889
01:26:41,520 --> 01:26:48,880
he couldn't get hold of it. Then there was another 
yell. If Buster hadn't been so frightened himself,  

890
01:26:48,880 --> 01:26:55,440
he might have recognized that second yell as 
one of fright, for that is what it was. You see  

891
01:26:55,440 --> 01:27:00,720
Farmer Brown's boy had just discovered Buster 
Bear. When he had yelled the first time,  

892
01:27:00,720 --> 01:27:05,600
he had supposed that it was one of the young 
cattle who live in the Old Pasture all summer,  

893
01:27:06,160 --> 01:27:12,800
but when he saw Buster, he was just as badly 
frightened as Buster himself. In fact, he was  

894
01:27:12,800 --> 01:27:20,560
too surprised and frightened even to run. After 
that second yell he just stood still and stared.

895
01:27:21,840 --> 01:27:25,760
Buster clawed at that awful thing on 
his head more frantically than ever.

896
01:27:26,720 --> 01:27:29,120
Suddenly it slipped off, so that he could see.  

897
01:27:30,240 --> 01:27:36,520
He gave one frightened look at Farmer 
Brown's boy, and then with a mighty "Woof!"  

898
01:27:37,920 --> 01:27:43,920
he started for the Green Forest as fast as his 
legs could take him, and this was very fast  

899
01:27:43,920 --> 01:27:50,000
indeed, let me tell you. He didn't stop to pick 
out a path, but just crashed through the bushes  

900
01:27:50,000 --> 01:27:56,400
as if they were nothing at all, just nothing 
at all. But the funniest thing of all is this—

901
01:27:57,280 --> 01:28:03,760
he took that pail with him! Yes, Sir, Buster 
Bear ran away with the big tin pail of Farmer  

902
01:28:03,760 --> 01:28:09,520
Brown's boy! You see when it slipped off his 
head, the handle was still around his neck,  

903
01:28:10,080 --> 01:28:16,320
and there he was running away with a pail 
hanging from his neck! He didn't want it.  

904
01:28:16,880 --> 01:28:23,040
He would have given anything to get rid of it. But 
he took it because he couldn't help it. And that  

