find a hiding place. So, when he reached the 
Green Forest, he kept right on to the deepest,  

935
01:31:34,080 --> 01:31:40,320
darkest, most lonesome part and crept under 
the thickest hemlock-tree he could find.

936
01:31:41,280 --> 01:31:48,240
But it was of no use. The sharp eyes of Sammy 
Jay and Blacky the Crow saw him. They actually  

937
01:31:48,240 --> 01:31:54,480
flew into the very tree under which he was 
hiding, and how they did scream! Pretty soon  

938
01:31:54,480 --> 01:32:01,200
Ol' Mistah Buzzard came dropping down out of the 
blue, blue sky and took a seat on a convenient  

939
01:32:01,200 --> 01:32:07,520
dead tree, where he could see all that went on. 
Ol' Mistah Buzzard began to grin as soon as he  

940
01:32:07,520 --> 01:32:15,120
saw that tin pail on Buster's neck. Then came 
others,—Redtail the Hawk, Scrapper the Kingbird,  

941
01:32:15,120 --> 01:32:22,080
Redwing the Blackbird, Drummer the Woodpecker, 
Welcome Robin, Tommy Tit the Chickadee, Jenny  

942
01:32:22,080 --> 01:32:28,640
Wren, Redeye the Vireo, and ever so many more. 
They came from the Old Orchard, the Green Meadows,  

943
01:32:28,640 --> 01:32:34,800
and even down by the Smiling Pool, for the voices 
of Sammy Jay and Blacky the Crow carried far,  

944
01:32:35,360 --> 01:32:40,800
and at the sound of them everybody hurried 
over, sure that something exciting was going on.

945
01:32:42,320 --> 01:32:48,720
Presently Buster heard light footsteps, and 
peeping out, he saw Billy Mink and Peter Rabbit  

946
01:32:48,720 --> 01:32:55,600
and Jumper the Hare and Prickly Porky 
and Reddy Fox and Jimmy Skunk. Even timid  

947
01:32:55,600 --> 01:33:00,560
little Whitefoot the Wood Mouse was where he 
could peer out and see without being seen.  

948
01:33:01,680 --> 01:33:06,000
Of course, Chatterer the Red Squirrel and 
Happy Jack the Gray Squirrel were there.  

949
01:33:06,720 --> 01:33:11,280
There they all sat in a great circle 
around him, each where he felt safe,  

950
01:33:11,280 --> 01:33:18,000
but where he could see, and every one of 
them laughing and making fun of Buster.

951
01:33:18,000 --> 01:33:25,360
"Thief, thief, thief!" screamed Sammy 
until his throat was sore. The worst of it  

952
01:33:25,360 --> 01:33:31,920
was Buster knew that everybody knew that it 
was true. That awful pail was proof of it.

953
01:33:33,440 --> 01:33:39,360
"I wish I never had thought of 
berries," growled Buster to himself.

954
01:33:41,200 --> 01:33:42,160
CHAPTER XXII

955
01:33:45,600 --> 01:33:47,760
BUSTER BEAR HAS A FIT OF TEMPER

956
01:33:48,880 --> 01:33:50,880
A temper is a bad, bad thing

957
01:33:50,880 --> 01:33:52,720
When once it gets away.

958
01:33:52,720 --> 01:33:54,480
There's nothing quite at all like it

959
01:33:54,480 --> 01:33:56,240
To spoil a pleasant day.

960
01:33:57,920 --> 01:34:03,920
Buster Bear was in a terrible temper. Yes, 
Sir, Buster Bear was having the worst fit of  

961
01:34:03,920 --> 01:34:09,040
temper ever seen in the Green Forest. And 
the worst part of it all was that all his  

962
01:34:09,040 --> 01:34:14,560
neighbors of the Green Forest and a whole lot 
from the Green Meadows and the Smiling Pool  

963
01:34:14,560 --> 01:34:20,640
were also there to see it. It is bad enough 
to give way to temper when you are all alone,  

964
01:34:20,640 --> 01:34:25,600
and there is no one to watch you, but 
when you let temper get the best of you  

965
01:34:25,600 --> 01:34:30,560
right where others see you, oh, dear, 
dear, it certainly is a sorry sight.

966
01:34:31,600 --> 01:34:37,280
Now ordinarily Buster is one of the most 
good-natured persons in the world. It takes a  

967
01:34:37,280 --> 01:34:43,520
great deal to rouse his temper. He isn't one tenth 
so quick tempered as Chatterer the Red Squirrel,  

968
01:34:43,520 --> 01:34:51,120
or Sammy Jay, or Reddy Fox. But when his temper 
is aroused and gets away from him, then watch  

969
01:34:51,120 --> 01:34:57,200
out! It seemed to Buster that he had had all 
that he could stand that day and a little more.  

970
01:34:58,000 --> 01:35:03,120
First had come the fright back there in the 
Old Pasture. Then the pail had slipped down  

971
01:35:03,120 --> 01:35:08,560
behind his ears and held fast, so he had run 
all the way to the Green Forest with it hanging  

972
01:35:08,560 --> 01:35:15,120
about his neck. This was bad enough, for he 
knew just how funny he must look, and besides,  

973
01:35:15,120 --> 01:35:22,640
it was very uncomfortable. But to have Sammy Jay 
call everybody within hearing to come and see him  

974
01:35:22,640 --> 01:35:28,960
was more than he could stand. It seemed to Buster 
as if everybody who lives in the Green Forest,  

975
01:35:28,960 --> 01:35:35,760
on the Green Meadows, or around the Smiling Brook, 
was sitting around his hiding place, laughing  

976
01:35:35,760 --> 01:35:41,840
and making fun of him. It was more than 
any self-respecting Bear could stand.

977
01:35:42,400 --> 01:35:47,120
With a roar of anger Buster Bear 
charged out of his hiding place.  

978
01:35:47,120 --> 01:35:53,120
He rushed this way and that way! He roared with 
all his might! He was very terrible to see.

979
01:35:54,160 --> 01:36:01,680
Those who could fly, flew. Those who could climb, 
climbed. And those who were swift of foot, ran.  

980
01:36:02,560 --> 01:36:08,320
A few who could neither fly nor climb nor 
run fast, hid and lay shaking and trembling  

981
01:36:08,320 --> 01:36:13,520
for fear that Buster would find them. In 
less time than it takes to tell about it,  

982
01:36:13,520 --> 01:36:17,440
Buster was alone. At least, 
he couldn't see any one.

983
01:36:17,440 --> 01:36:19,120
Illus Those who could fly, flew. 
Those who could climb, climbed.

984
01:36:19,120 --> 01:36:25,360
Then he vented his temper on the tin pail. He 
cuffed at it and pulled at it, all the time  

985
01:36:25,360 --> 01:36:30,240
growling angrily. He lay down and 
clawed at it with his hind feet.  

986
01:36:31,040 --> 01:36:36,960
At last the handle broke, and 
he was free! He shook himself.  

987
01:36:37,600 --> 01:36:44,640
Then he jumped on the helpless pail. With a blow 
of a big paw he sent it clattering against a tree.  

988
01:36:45,440 --> 01:36:52,000
He tried to bite it. Then he once more 
fell to knocking it this way and that way,  

989
01:36:52,000 --> 01:36:59,200
until it was pounded flat, and no one would 
ever have guessed that it had once been a pail.

990
01:37:00,400 --> 01:37:05,840
Then, and not till then, did Buster 
recover his usual good nature.  

991
01:37:06,480 --> 01:37:15,120
Little by little, as he thought it all over, a 
look of shame crept into his face. "I—I guess  

992
01:37:15,120 --> 01:37:22,320
it wasn't the fault of that thing. I ought to 
have known enough to keep my head out of it,"

993
01:37:23,200 --> 01:37:25,360
he said slowly and thoughtfully.

994
01:37:26,640 --> 01:37:30,720
"You got no more than you deserve for 
stealing Farmer Brown's boy's berries,"

995
01:37:31,360 --> 01:37:35,680
said Sammy Jay, who had come back and 
was looking on from the top of a tree.

996
01:37:36,400 --> 01:37:40,800
"You ought to know by this time 
that no good comes of stealing."

997
01:37:42,800 --> 01:37:48,160
Buster Bear looked up and grinned, 
and there was a twinkle in his eyes.  

998
01:37:48,160 --> 01:37:54,400
"You ought to know, Sammy Jay," said 
he. "I hope you'll always remember it."

999
01:37:54,400 --> 01:37:59,920
"Thief, thief, thief!" 
screamed Sammy, and flew away.

1000
01:38:01,680 --> 01:38:02,720
CHAPTER XXIII

1001
01:38:06,320 --> 01:38:08,800
FARMER BROWN'S BOY LUNCHES ON

1002
01:38:08,800 --> 01:38:09,280
BERRIES

1003
01:38:10,400 --> 01:38:12,480
When things go wrong in spite of you

1004
01:38:12,480 --> 01:38:14,800
To smile's the best thing you can do—

1005
01:38:15,520 --> 01:38:18,640
To smile and say, "I'm mighty glad

1006
01:38:18,640 --> 01:38:21,600
They are no worse; they're not so bad!"

1007
01:38:23,200 --> 01:38:26,960
That is what Farmer Brown's boy 
said when he found that Buster Bear  

1008
01:38:26,960 --> 01:38:33,600
had stolen the berries he had worked so hard to 
pick and then had run off with the pail. You see,  

1009
01:38:33,600 --> 01:38:39,920
Farmer Brown's boy is learning to be something of 
a philosopher, one of those people who accept bad  

1010
01:38:39,920 --> 01:38:45,840
things cheerfully and right away see how they 
are better than they might have been. When he  

1011
01:38:45,840 --> 01:38:51,040
had first heard some one in the bushes where he 
had hidden his pail of berries, he had been very  

1012
01:38:51,040 --> 01:38:55,920
sure that it was one of the cows or young cattle 
who live in the Old Pasture during the summer.

1013
01:38:56,640 --> 01:39:01,840
He had been afraid that they might stupidly 
kick over the pail and spill the berries,  

1014
01:39:01,840 --> 01:39:04,720
and he had hurried to drive whoever it was away.  

1015
01:39:05,680 --> 01:39:10,000
It hadn't entered his head that it could 
be anybody who would eat those berries.

1016
01:39:10,000 --> 01:39:14,880
When he had yelled and Buster Bear had suddenly 
appeared, struggling to get off the pail which  

1017
01:39:14,880 --> 01:39:20,160
had caught over his head, Farmer Brown's 
boy had been too frightened to even move.  

1018
01:39:21,120 --> 01:39:26,240
Then he had seen Buster tear away through 
the brush even more frightened than he was,  

1019
01:39:26,240 --> 01:39:29,280
and right away his courage had begun to come back.

1020
01:39:30,720 --> 01:39:34,880
"If he is so afraid of me, I 
guess I needn't be afraid of him,"  

1021
01:39:35,600 --> 01:39:41,520
said he. "I've lost my berries, but it is 
worth it to find out that he is afraid of me.  

1022
01:39:42,480 --> 01:39:48,240
There are plenty more on the bushes, and all I've 
got to do is to pick them. It might be worse."

1023
01:39:49,600 --> 01:39:54,400
He walked over to the place where the pail 
had been, and then he remembered that when  

1024
01:39:54,400 --> 01:40:00,160
Buster ran away he had carried the pail with 
him, hanging about his neck. He whistled.  

1025
01:40:00,880 --> 01:40:06,960
It was a comical little whistle of chagrin as 
he realized that he had nothing in which to put  

1026
01:40:06,960 --> 01:40:14,240
more berries, even if he picked them. "It's worse 
than I thought," cried he. "That bear has cheated  

1027
01:40:14,240 --> 01:40:21,360
me out of that berry pie my mother promised me." 
Then he began to laugh, as he thought of how funny

1028
01:40:21,360 --> 01:40:27,360
Buster Bear had looked with the pail about his 
neck, and then because, you know he is learning  

1029
01:40:27,360 --> 01:40:34,960
to be a philosopher, he once more repeated, "It 
might have been worse. Yes, indeed, it might have  

1030
01:40:34,960 --> 01:40:42,000
been worse. That bear might have tried to eat me 
instead of the berries. I guess I'll go eat that  

1031
01:40:42,000 --> 01:40:50,080
lunch I left back by the spring, and then I'll 
go home. I can pick berries some other day."

1032
01:40:50,080 --> 01:40:55,760
Chuckling happily over Buster Bear's great fright, 
Farmer Brown's boy tramped back to the spring  

1033
01:40:55,760 --> 01:41:01,520
where he had left two thick sandwiches on a flat 
stone when he started to save his pail of berries.  

1034
01:41:02,800 --> 01:41:04,880
"My, but those sandwiches will taste good,"

1035
01:41:05,440 --> 01:41:10,640
thought he. "I'm glad they are big and 
thick. I never was hungrier in my life.

1036
01:41:12,240 --> 01:41:19,040
Hello!" This he exclaimed right out loud, 
for he had just come in sight of the flat  

1037
01:41:19,040 --> 01:41:23,680
stone where the sandwiches should 
have been, and they were not there.  

1038
01:41:24,960 --> 01:41:29,360
No, Sir, there wasn't so much as a crumb 
left of those two thick sandwiches.  

1039
01:41:30,560 --> 01:41:38,160
You see, Old Man Coyote had found them and 
gobbled them up while Farmer Brown's boy was away.

1040
01:41:39,360 --> 01:41:45,360
But Farmer Brown's boy didn't know anything about 
Old Man Coyote. He rubbed his eyes and stared  

1041
01:41:45,360 --> 01:41:50,240
everywhere, even up in the trees, as if he thought 
those sandwiches might be hanging up there.  

1042
01:41:51,360 --> 01:41:56,320
They had disappeared as completely as if 
they never had been, and Old Man Coyote had  

1043
01:41:56,320 --> 01:42:04,320
taken care to leave no trace of his visit. Farmer 
Brown's boy gaped foolishly this way and that way.  

1044
01:42:05,200 --> 01:42:11,440
Then, instead of growing angry, a slow 
smile stole over his freckled face.  

1045
01:42:12,800 --> 01:42:19,760
"I guess some one else was hungry too," he 
muttered. "Wonder who it was? Guess this  

1046
01:42:19,760 --> 01:42:25,120
Old Pasture is no place for me to-day. I'll 
fill up on berries and then I'll go home."

1047
01:42:26,400 --> 01:42:32,320
So Farmer Brown's boy made his lunch on 
blueberries and then rather sheepishly he  

1048
01:42:32,320 --> 01:42:37,040
started for home to tell of all the strange 
things that had happened to him in the Old  

1049
01:42:37,040 --> 01:42:44,480
Pasture. Two or three times, as he trudged along, 
he stopped to scratch his head thoughtfully. "I  

1050
01:42:44,480 --> 01:42:52,240
guess," said he at last, "that I'm not so smart as 
I thought I was, and I've got a lot to learn yet."

1051
01:42:53,840 --> 01:42:57,680
This is the end of the adventures 
of Buster Bear in this book  

1052
01:42:57,680 --> 01:43:05,280
because—guess why. Because Old Mr. Toad insists 
that I must write a book about his adventures,  

1053
01:43:05,280 --> 01:43:11,280
and Old Mr. Toad is such a good friend 
of all of us that I am going to do it.

1054
01:43:11,280 --> 01:43:12,930
- THE END -

